<HEADLINE> Singapore Police: Bomb Threat Against Americans A Hoax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Singapore police said Monday
evening that investigations have revealed that a bomb threat call
against the American community in the city state turned out to be
a hoax.
</P>
<P>
The police made the confirmation in a response to the U.S.
Embassy in Singapore and the Singapore American Club that
contacted the police Monday afternoon after the embassy received a
bomb threat call.
</P>
<P>
The American Club was closed after it was informed by the U.S.
Embassy of what it called "non-specific threats to the American
Community" at about noon.
</P>
<P>
The Television Corporation of Singapore quoted a spokesman from
the American Club as saying that it took about 15 minutes to
evacuate more than 1,000 people from the Club.
</P>
<P>
The club will resume business as usual Tuesday, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
The police warned that delivering a false message, like a bomb
threat, is punishable with a fine of up to 50,000 Singapore
dollars (about 30,000 U.S dollars) and imprisonment of up to seven
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
