<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Not to Meet Soeharto: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian State
Secretary/Minister Akbar Tanjung Monday ruled out the possibility
of a meeting between President B.J. Habibie and his predecessor,
Soeharto, for a "national dialogue."
</P>
<P>
There could never be a meeting among Habibie, former president
Soeharto, Nahdlatul Ulama leader Abdurrahman Wahid and Armed
Forces Commander Gen. Wiranto, Tanjung told reporters at the
presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on Wahid's efforts to bring about a meeting
among the four for a "national dialogue" to solve the nation's
political problems.
</P>
<P>
Wahid had already met Gen. Wiranto and Soeharto in preparation
of the proposed dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Tanjung said a meeting between Habibie and former president
Soeharto was always possible but only in the nature of a "social
get-together."
</P>
<P>
He said Habibie neither had any plan to hold a dialogue with
the other leaders minus Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
"I believe such a meeting won't happen because Habibie has
positioned himself as a president who will implement the People's
Consultative Assembly (MPR) resolutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tanjung said the MPR was the highest council of state so a
national dialogue is best held in the MPR where figures from the
various regions of Indonesia also have seats. "A dialogue in the
assembly would be the most constitutional of all possible
dialogues," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
