<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urgent: Security Council Begins Meeting on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council was meeting to consider its relations with Iraq,
focusing on economic sanctions, arms inspections and a relief
program intended to aid Iraqis suffering under an economic
embargo, U.N. officials said Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
This is Security Council's first meeting on Iraq after the
United States and Britain announced to end their military Strikes
on December 19.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. diplomats, the 15-member Council is
sharply divided in these issues.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats said the difficulty the Council faces is that the
negotiated resolutions on Iraq have linked the sanctions,
inspections and the "oil-for-food" plan that will be hard to
separate.
</P>
<P>
The Council may take the first step to start a full review of
United Nations relations with Iraq, but this is unlikely to happen
until the next year, the diplomats added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
