<HEADLINE> Israeli Knesset Passes Bill Abolishing Direct Election of PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Knesset
(parliament) passed its first reading here Monday of the bill
abolishing direct election of prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset met here Monday to vote on a bill calling for early
elections in the country. But the Knesset members voted first on a
bill abolishing direct election of prime ministers, which was
jointly sponsored by Yossi Beilin, Knesset member from the
oppositon Labor party, and Uzi Landau, another Knesset member from
the ruling Likud party.
</P>
<P>
The bill was passed by a vote of 62 - 54 in the first reading.
It will be sent back to the Knesset Law Committee for preparations
for its second and thrid readings in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Following the voting, Prime Minister Benjamin Netnayahu took
the floor to deliver the government's policy statement concerning
the peace process and his view on the bill calling for early
elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources here said that during the Likud meeting held
earlier Monday, the majority of the ruling Likud Knesset members
decided to vote in favor of the bill calling for early elections.
</P>
<P>
The vote on this bill will take place later Monday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
