<HEADLINE> Iraq Hails Jordanian Parliament's Pro-Iraq Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) Chairman Saadoun Hammadi Monday praised the Jordanian
parliament for approving a decision calling on its government to
break the U.N. embargo imposed on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Hammadi made the remarks in a letter to Speaker of Jordanian
House of Representatives Abdu Hadi Majali.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Hammadi also called on Arab parliaments to
pursue a pro-Arab stance to support the Iraqi people who are
facing the forces of evil and aggression, the Iraqi News agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq following its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990. The sanctions will not be lifted until the
U.N. Special Commission, which monitors Iraq's disarmament,
certifies that Iraq has cleared off all weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The commission has repeatedly run into standoffs with Iraq and
the latest one has led to four nights of U.S.-British air strikes
on Iraq last week.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian Times reported Monday that the parliament
unanimously decided to break the embargo on Iraq, and called on
its government and other Arab governments to defy it and hold an
Arab summit to discuss the joint U.S.-British aggression against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian parliament voiced total solidarity with Iraq and
its people and strongly denounced "the barbaric attacks
perpetrated" by the U.S. and British governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
