<HEADLINE> IMF Sees Global Economic Growth Slower but Mood Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) issued a supplementary World Economic Outlook here
Monday provided a little slower growth revision but asserted
general mood has improved from three months ago.
</P>
<P>
The IMF 169-page joint interim World Economic Outlook and
International Capital Markets said that while the danger of a
world-wide recession does seem to have diminished, it would be
premature to consider the global economy's difficulties to be
over.
</P>
<P>
The IMF report lowered its 1999 world growth forecast down to
2.2 percent or 2.3 percent as compared with a 2.5 percent growth
predicted in the previous report released in September.
</P>
<P>
However, thanks to a number of steps taken recently, which
include interest rate cuts around the world and a large IMF-led
international rescue package to Brazil, the general mood was less
somber than three months ago.
</P>
<P>
For some countries, including Japan, Brazil and Russia, the
outlook has deteriorated more significantly. The growth
projections for some of the Asian emerging market economies in
crisis have also been lowered somewhat further, indicating that
the improved prospects for recovery may not materialize until well
into 1999. An exception is Thailand, where GDP is now projected to
rise steadily, though slowly, throughout 1999, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The document notes that "among the most encouraging aspects of
the baseline scenario are the continued solid growth performance,
despite modest downward revisions, of the United States and the
future euro area, although there are downside risks in both
cases."
</P>
<P>
Additionally, the IMF new report also raised its growth
projection for China, which reflecting stronger-than-expected
performance in the second half of 1998, partly in response to
policy stimulus. "In China and Hong Kong SAR, the successful
maintenance of the exchange regimes has helped to restore
stability in Asian financial markets," the IMF noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
