<HEADLINE> 9.2 Million Pounds Awarded for Road Crash Victim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A Dutch student completely
paralyzed in a road accident was awarded damages of 9.2 million
pounds, the High Court in London ruled on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Martijn Biesheuvel had hopes of a high-flying career in
business destroyed by the crash, the court was told.
</P>
<P>
The payout is the largest personal injury award made by an
English court.
</P>
<P>
Biesheuvel was 22 and had just finished final exams in business
administration at Bath University in May 1994 when a car in which
he was traveling with four friends collided with parked vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Nobody else was seriously hurt in the crash in the city.
</P>
<P>
The insurers of driver Andrew Birrell will pay the award, which
includes loss of future earnings and the cost of care.
</P>
<P>
It was accepted that Birrell's negligence caused the crash.
</P>
<P>
Biesheuvel was not wearing a rear seatbelt but in court,
Justice Eady said: "I am wholly unpersuaded that I should make a
finding of contributory negligence against Mr Biesheuvel."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
