<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multi-sectoral Approach to AIDS Urged in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean National AIDS
Coordinating Program (NACP) is calling for a multi-sectoral
approach to create AIDS awareness and avoid further spread of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
The approach would invite government ministries, churches and
non-governmental organizations to participate in AIDS awareness
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Zimbabwe News Agency here Monday,
NACP youth coordinator, Zorodzai Gumbie said the magnitude of
human life devastation by AIDS is making it imperative that
everyone should play a part in finding the means to curb the
disease.
</P>
<P>
"Responsibility should not be left to the Ministry of Health
and Child Welfare alone but every one should cooperate," Gumbie
said.
</P>
<P>
She stressed the need to intensify campaigns in rural areas
where there was limited media access.
</P>
<P>
Gumbie added that AIDS education should be made imperative at
every level of the existing education structures in schools to
equip children with enough information about AIDS before they
contracted it.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is the second to Botswana on the world list of
countries worst affected by AIDS. About 1.4 million adults, 25.8
percent of sexually active adults between 15 and 49 years are
thought to be HIV positive. More than 700 people die every week
from HIV/AIDS-related illnesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
