<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Have not Lost Hope With Libya on Lockerbie Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said on Monday that it is regrettable that the
Lockerbie issue had not been solved before the 10th anniversary,
which falls on Monday, but he is still hopeful to get positive
response from Libya on the 1988 Locker bombing.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon his arrival at the U.N. headquarters
here on Monday morning, Annan said, "My message to them (the
families of victims) is that it is regrettable that 10 years after
the event, we have not been able to get to the truth so that they
can put this behind them, mourn their dead and carry on with their
lives."
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remarks on the 10th anniversary of the Lockerbie
bombing, which involved the explosion of a Pam Am airliner over
Lockerbie, Scotland, taking 270 lives.
</P>
<P>
"But I am still hopeful that we will get a positive decision
from the Libyan Government," he said, "I had hoped it would come
before this date -- the anniversary -- but I have not lost hope.
And they should not."
</P>
<P>
Annan, who paid a visit to Libya in early December, failed to
persuade Libya into surrendering the two suspects, but the U.N.
chief remains hopeful for a proper solution.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan top legislature, the Libyan General People's
Congress, issued a statement on December 15, calling for a
peaceful solution to the Lockerbie bombing, and calling on the
United States and Britain to clear away all obstacles in the trial
of the two suspects.
</P>
<P>
Libyan has agreed to let the two suspected Libyans be tried
before a Scottish court in the Netherlands, but it held that the
two Libyans, if convicted, should not serve their sentences in
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Libya has been under U.N. sanctions since 1992 for failing to
hand over to the trial of the Netherland-based court two suspects
in the Lockerbie bombing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
