<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chief U.N. Arms Inspector Says Not to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Chief U.N. arms
inspector Richard Butler said on Monday that he would stay in his
post despite Iraq's strong call for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has accused Butler, Executive Chairman of the United
Nations Special Commission in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons
of mass destruction, of coordinating with the United States by
reporting that Iraq had failed to cooperate fully with the United
Nations, which directly led to the four-day U.S. military strikes
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Butler said "Any suggestion that I
cooked the books or colluded with the Untied States for this
purpose is without foundation."
</P>
<P>
"I could take you through site by site and I can show you that
in every case there was a disarmament justification for going to
that site. They were my choices. They were based on facts. I did
not discuss them with the Unite States or anyone else," he said.
</P>
<P>
Butler said he would not resign in the face of the criticism.
</P>
<P>
"Now there is no reason for me to do that. The very idea that
my presence in this job can be used as a diversion from Iraq's
failure to give us the information we need... that somehow this
comes down to one individual, I am sorry that is such a
diversionary tactic and there would be no reason to resign in the
face of that," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
