<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Russian Ambassadors to Return to U.S., </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian Ambassador to the
United States Yuly Vorontsov will probably return to Washington in
"one to two days," Interfax reported Monday, quoting Foreign
Ministry sources.
</P>
<P>
Vorontsov and Russian Ambassador to Britain, Yuri Fokin, were
recalled last Friday for consultations in light of U.S.-British
airstrikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The recalls were seen as a protest against the missile raids,
which Moscow has all along staunchly opposed.
</P>
<P>
Fokin will probably return to London this week, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
The ambassadors will resume their work "because they have
completed their consultations in Moscow," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Moscow reacted angrily at the military actions, which President
Boris Yeltsin said had "flagrantly violated the United Nations
Charter" and norms of international law.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Interfax quoted a source in the
Russian Foreign Ministry said Monday that Moscow will not propose
that the U.N. Security Council adopt a draft resolution to condemn
the U.S.-British strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Russia's position on this military operation is clear. But the
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council have the veto
power," the source said.
</P>
<P>
However, at the U.N. Security Council's meeting on Monday
evening, Moscow time, Russia will insist that further steps be
taken to ensure the implementation of the council's resolutions on
Iraq by all sides and that political methods be found to deal with
the situation in the wake of the air strikes, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Russia is not going to insist that the U.N. Security Council
lift international sanctions against Iraq at the present time, but
it will propose that humanitarian aid to Iraq be discussed,
Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Slim Chance Seen for U.K.'s Containment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Although British Prime Minister
Tony Blair expressed his confidence in a "policy of containment"
on Iraq, dim prospect can be seen in the implementation of the
strategy due to growing domestic and international divergences.
</P>
<P>
Citing the three-day air strikes against Iraq which he noted
has realized all expected objectives, Blair said Sunday that
Saddam's strength and Iraq's capability to produce and use weapons
of mass destruction were decimated, which provided the best
opportunity for further containment on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The three main points of the strategy include further military
strikes when necessary, more intensive enforcement of sanctions
and the dispatch of the British aircraft carrier "Invincible" to
the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Blair said Britain would strengthen its cooperation with the
U.N. Security Council, the Gulf countries and the European Unions
members, and would continue to assist the Iraq opposition to help
remove Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The new strategy sounds good, but analysts here cast pessimism
on its expected results.
</P>
<P>
Blair's opposition Conservatives have already pounced on
apparent discrepancies in his vision and reality.
</P>
<P>
"He (Blair) called for a more intensive enforcement of sanctions,
but how is that any easier today than it was a week ago?" asked a
Conservative spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it won't be easy now to get support from Britain's
partners in Europe to reinforce the sanctions. French President
Jacques Chirac called for a review on Sunday of the eight-year oil
embargo against Baghdad in order to improve living conditions for
the people in Iraq. The same words had been heard even before the
strikes were launched.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the U.S. bypassed the U.N. Security Council in
ordering the air strikes, making some members of the Security
Council outrage at the ignorance. China condemned the military
action and Russia called back its ambassadors to the U.S. and
Britain to protest against the strikes. Time will be needed to
repair Britain's relations with the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Repair work will also be needed on Britain's image in the
Islamic and Arab world, where governments have been unwilling to
support the Blair-Clinton strategy since the attacks were
unleashed shortly before the outset of the muslim holy month of
Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
It's also hard to say how much Britain can rely on Iraq
opposition groups. Britain tried to persuade members of Iraq's
fragmented opposition to work together last month but they still
failed to combine their strengths to oust Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
British reinforcements in the Gulf won't do much to suppress
Iraq. The United States and Britain have been keeping their forces
in that region for years, but little has been done to prevent
Saddam Hussein from playing the "cat and mouse game." What can they
possibly expect to achieve by sending one more aircraft carrier
there? 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
