<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Likely to Settle Name Disputes With Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Greece is likely to settle its
disputes with Macedonia by accepting the name "Republic of
Macedonia-Skopje" for the neighboring Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a Parliament debate Monday, Stelios Papathemelis, a
ruling party MP for Thessaloniki, said that the Greek government
appeared to be ready to accept the name for the Former Yugoslav
Republic of Macedonia (FYROM), according to the semi-official
Athens News Agency (ANA).
</P>
<P>
Papathemelis said that he got a document issued recently by the
Greek Finance Ministry's customs department showing that the code
for Macedonia would change from the present XJ to MK as of January
1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Macedonia have been at odds for years over their
disputes of the name of "Macedonia" because Athens opposes the use
by Skopje of the name "Macedonia," saying that it conceals
expansionist designs against its northern province of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two neighboring countries have been
improving in recent years, especially since they signed an interim
agreement in New York in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two countries agreed to continue their
U.N.-sponsored negotiations to find a mutually acceptable solution
for the name issue.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between Greece and Macedonia is expected to exceed
250 million U.S. dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greek government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas said Monday that he was not aware of the documents cited by
Papathemelis while stressing that the solution of the name issue
with Skopje was being sought within the framework of negotiations
being conducted under U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos will on Tuesday
begin his one-day visit to Macedonia and have talks with
Macedonian government officials on ways of improving bilateral
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
