<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Civil Service Urged to Fully Implement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi said Monday that much is expected from the civil
service in successfully implementing policies adopted by
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting organized here to discuss ways to ensure
the participation of government offices in the on-going civil
service reform program, which was attended by ministers and heads
of various government offices, Meles urged the civil service to
see to it that the policies are put into effect.
</P>
<P>
The official Ethiopian News Agency quoted Meles as saying that
the civil service reform program would help ensure quality of
services, circumvent mis-demeanour and find a way to reward
competent civil servant.
</P>
<P>
Meles stressed the need to boost capacity in order to properly
execute on-going development activities and emphasised the role
of the civil service reform program in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The civil service inherited from previous regimes not only
failed to execute the decisions of parliament, but also
regard itself as a policy maker, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meles noted that building a mass-based federal system is one
important task in the political field, adding that rehabilitating
the economy and helping farmers who account for 85 percent of the
total population of the country be beneficiaries of social
services are also priority areas.
</P>
<P>
He added that a competent executive body is important to
guarantee success in the socio-economic and political fields.
</P>
</TEXT>
