<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Expounds Peace Policy in Crucial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- At a crucial meeting of the
Israeli Knesset (parliament), Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
Monday expounded his policy in the peace talks with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The plenum of the Knesset, which opened Monday afternoon, is
due to vote later on a bill calling for dissolution of the
Knesset and early elections.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that Israel had handed over some
territories to the Palestinians in the first phase of the
withdrawal according to the Wye peace accord signed with the
Palestinians two months ago.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) failed
to fulfill its commitments to fight terrorism and avoid
unilateral activities.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu reiterated his conditions to further implement the
agreement, which were approved by the Israeli cabinet on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the conditions, the PNA must stop violence
against Israel, collect all illegal weapons in the territories,
reduce the number of the Palestinian police, renounce unilateral
statement over statehood and agree to Israel's stance on the
release of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that most of the Israeli people support his
policy. And he called on the opposition Labor Party to express
support too.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that if his policy will not be favored
by a majority of the Knesset, the Knesset should be dissolved
and early elections should be held.
</P>
<P>
He also said that at his request the no-confidence motion,
which was added on the early elections bill two weeks ago,
will not be included in the vote.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ruling Likud Party announced on Monday that
it will also vote for the early elections bill.
</P>
<P>
If the bill is approved by the Knesset, the Knesset will
be dissolved and the elections for prime minister will be held
within six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
