<HEADLINE> CIS Defense Chiefs Condemn U.S.-British Strikes on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Defense
Ministers of CIS Countries on Monday condemned the U.S.-British
airstrikes against Iraq as "a totally unjustified act of
aggression."
</P>
<P>
The ministers, in a joint statement, said the strikes "resulted
in serious civilian casualties and aggravated the military and
political situation in the world."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting earlier Monday, Russian Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev urged his fellow ministers to improve and
reform the CIS body and step up military cooperation in light of
the strikes on Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"Due to the unpredictability of the U.S. policy and the policy
of its allies, the CIS Defense Ministers Council must arrive at a
unanimous understanding of the current military-political problems
and must work out a common stand on the prospects for the
promotion of their military cooperation," Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
Delegations of 10 of the 12-member CIS countries are attending
the meeting. Moldova and Kyrgyzstan did not send their
representatives. 
</P>
