<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Appoints New Army Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's new cabinet Monday
issued the first batch of appointments for key posts, including
the country's army commander.
</P>
<P>
Brig. Gen. Michel Suleiman, a Maronite Catholic, was promoted
to full general and named as the new army commander to replace
Gen. Emile Lahoud.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud, also a Maronite Catholic, was elected president on
October 15 after nine years of service as army commander.
</P>
<P>
The appointment was announced by Information Minister Anwar
Khalil following the first meeting of the cabinet of 16
predominantly technocrat ministers since it won a vote of
confidence in Parliament last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Brig. Jamil El-Sayyed, Shiite Muslim, was promoted to
Lt. General and named head of the General Security Department.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time since Lebanon gained independence from
France 55 years ago that a Shiite Muslim takes this sensitive post
from Maronite.
</P>
<P>
According to Lebanon's constitution, the top posts should be
equally divided among Sunni Muslims, Shiite Muslims and Maronite
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
The country's president always comes from Maronite, prime
minister from Sunni Muslim and house speaker from Shiite Muslim.
</P>
<P>
Catholic Brig. Edward Mansour was promoted to Lt. General and
appointed chief of the State Security Department, a traditionally
Shiite post.
</P>
<P>
Brig. Abdulkarim Ibrahim, a Sunni, was promoted to Lt. General
and named police chief, while Brig. Nasser Rahban, a Maronite, was
named commander of the gendarmerie, countryside police.
</P>
<P>
Observers praised the appointments, saying the new government
is trying to break the country's traditionally sectarian politics
and appoint top officials on the basis of their qualifications
and honesty, rather than along their religious lines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on Healing Work in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said on Monday that he will try to get Security Council
members together to work out the ways of dealing with the
situation after U.S. and British military attacks against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"It is not helpful that the Council is divided, and I would
hope that in the weeks ahead we will find a way of bringing
everyone together, so that we can carry on the essential work of
the Council," Annan told reporters when entering the U.N.
headquarters Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
He said he had been on the phone with some of the leaders
around the world over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The four-day military strikes without a U.N. endorsement, have
been blasted by several Council members as the actions are against
the U.N. Charter and the norms guiding international relations.
</P>
<P>
Annan said Wednesday, when the air-strikes began, "it is a sad
day for the U.N. and the world". The actions ended on Saturday,
leaving the Council heavy divided on issues relating to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
On the resumption of U.N. arms inspections in Iraq, Annan said
he believes that the answer to the question of whether a new
inspection mechanism should emerge will come out after Council
discussions.
</P>
<P>
Council members, including Russia and China, have criticized
chief U.N. arms inspector Richard Butler for his biased report
which the U.S. and Britain took as the pretext to launch military
actions. France has called for a new inspection organization and
new methods of inspection.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi officials said if the prolonged sanctions against Iraq
continue in their current form, no inspections will be allowed,
especially under Butler.
</P>
<P>
"You've heard all the discussions going on -- several
governments saying that we need a new structure, we need a new
inspection mechanism," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know what that means, I don't know what that entails,
and I don't know what kind of structure they have in mind. But it
will emerge after the discussions," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Council began their first post-Iraqi-bombing closed-door
session Monday morning on its relations with Iraq, focusing on
economic sanctions, arms inspections and a relief program intended
to aid Iraqis suffering under the eight-year sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Without giving details, Annan said he had sent a message to
Deputy Iraqi Prime Minister Tariq Aziz through his special envoy
Prakash Shah and he is waiting for a reaction.
</P>
<P>
A senior U.N. official said U.N. relief workers evacuated after
the anti-Iraq military actions are expected to come back to
Baghdad by Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aziz Explains Casualties in U.S.-British Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz called the U.S.-British air strikes against Iraq as a
"criminal aggression" aimed at bringing country back to the
pre-industrial age.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference here Monday that 38 of the
Republican Guards died and 100 wounded during the intensive air
strikes from Wednesday to Saturday. The elite guards were
considered as a strong pillar of the Iraqi regime and one of the
main targets of the air raids.
</P>
<P>
As to the casualties of the army, he said that 65 died and 180
injured.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not give the exact figure of civilian
casualties, saying the damage was similar to that in the 1991 Gulf
War and the almost all the industrial sites were pounded.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. and Britain targeted civilian and government
buildings, radio and TV facilities, communication institutions,
hospitals and schools.
</P>
<P>
He accused the two countries of carrying out their "imperialist
and colonialist" policy against Iraq and tramping on international
laws and all moral norms.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will "never, never accept any condition made by
(U.S. President Bill) Clinton and (British Prime Minister Tony)
Blair as to a resumption of UNSCOM work in Iraq, Aziz said. The
U.N. Special Commission oversees the destruction of all prohibited
weapons in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
When the U.S. and Britain bombed Iraq, "they killed UNSCOM," he
said. "UNSCOM is their own casualty, not ours," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Lifting the sanctions completely is Iraq's solution to the
situation," he said. The crippling sanctions was imposed on Iraq
after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
"After the comprehensive and severe aggression in 1991,
thousands of interviews, thousands of inspections, the imposition
of no-fly zones, there came the Operation Desert Fox. so how the
United states and Britain expect to resume weapons inspections? "
he asked.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq strongly believes that the United States has
only suspended the attack and not ended it.
</P>
<P>
In fact, he said, the aggression never stopped since the 1991
Gulf War to evict Iraq out of Kuwait, and cited the economic
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"It has never stopped. It has taken different chapters, " he
said.
</P>
<P>
He ridiculed Clinton for saying that the United States took
Islamic sensitivities into consideration while planning the attack
and ending it on the first day of the holy month of Ramadan when
Muslims are required to fast.
</P>
<P>
"The question is not Ramadan, The question is that they had
assembled a limited amount of assets ... and they wanted to make a
swift and quick aggression, " he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that to contain Iraq from development is the conspiracy
of the United states and Zionists, who take the Arabs as whole as
their enemies in this region, "Iraq is the first and Syria and
Libya may be their next targets."
</P>
<P>
On the fate of UNSCOM, he said that the current UNSCOM is not a
body of the U.N. Security Council, because the U.N. chief Kofi
Annan does not know its activities. UNSCOM has been serving as a
tool in the imperialists' hands against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
As to the U.S. statements to change the government of Iraq, he
said that the Iraqi government is a free and independent
government. It has nothing to do with the U.S. as what kind of
government Iraq should have. He said that the U.S. is determined
to change Iraqi government because Iraq has not done anything to
bring down the oil prices from 21 dollars a barrel to less than 10
dollars. Instead, it has been challenging the U.S. imperialist
policies which seeking hegemony in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is foolish to believe that sending several
hundreds of missiles on Iraq would trigger uprising against the
Iraqi government. He said that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein is
beloved by the Iraqi people for the past decades and he is still
the strong and trusted leader of the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> November Industrial Output Drops 9.1 Percent in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia's industrial output
stood at 161 billion rubles (7.6 billion U.S. dollars) in
November, down 9.1 percent from the same period last year, the
State Statistics Committee said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the first eleven months of the year, overall industrial
output dropped by 5.0 percent as compared with the same period of
1997, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
All industrial branches in the first eleven months of 1998,
except the polygraphic industry, showed signs of decline. The
production of electricity dropped by 1.6 percent, fuel by 2.7
percent, ferrous metals by 8.4 percent, non-ferrous metals by 4.7
percent, chemicals and petroleum products by 7.1 percent, machines
and metal parts 7.6 percent, wood, timber, pulp and paper by 26.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Materov, the first deputy economics minister, sounded
optimistic, saying that industrial decline will end between the
first and second half of next year.
</P>
<P>
He said the devaluation of the ruble will be one of the factors
of the forthcoming production growth, as a weaker ruble helped
boost export and cut down import.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Agricultural production in January to November
decreased by 9.0 percent and the country registered the worst
harvest in more than four decades.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary reports, Russia's gross grain
harvest was 48.5 million tons, 45.3 percent down from 1997's
figure of 88.6 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Temporarily Suspends Privatization Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's parliament has
resolved that the privatization process of public enterprises be
temporarily suspended.
</P>
<P>
Members of parliament made the resolution Monday after winding
up a debate on the report of the select committee on
privatization, the Radio Uganda reported this evening.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made in response to reports of rampant
corruption of senior government officials in the privatization
exercise following Major General Salim Saleh's recent confession
of irregular purchase of Uganda Commercial Bank (UCB).
</P>
<P>
Saleh, a former senior presidential advisor on defense and
security and younger brother of President Yoweri Museveni, was
found to have bought UCB fraudulently two weeks ago, which, in
Museveni's words, raised the curtain for the country's renewed
fight against corruption.
</P>
<P>
During Monday's session, MPs also resolved that the president
relieve Sam Kuteesa, who is State Minister in charge of
investment, of his duties in government should he declines to
resign.
</P>
<P>
They wanted the sales contract of Trans-Ocean, UCB and Uganda
Airlines revoked forthwith because corruption is reported to be
found in the sale of these big parastatals of the country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's divestiture account had a balance of only 4.8 million
U.S. Dollars by September 30 although the 87 parastatals so far
sold have fetched some 110.8 million Dollars for the state
coffers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beckenbauer: Germans Football Have Lost Their Supremacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- German football-team has lost its
position as one of the world's soccer powers, The "Emperor" of the
German Football Franz Beckenbauer said in a German sports magazine
 published Monday.
</P>
<P>
Beckenbauer, who was the German national team-captain of the 1974
World Cup winners and coach of the 1990 world champions, is now the
Bayern Munixh president.
</P>
<P>
He told in a interview of the magazine, the Germans had been "too
complacent" and other countries had now overtaken them.
</P>
<P>
European champions Germany have won the World Cup three times - in
1954, 1974 and 1990 - and have also been losing finalists three times,
but played disappointingly at France 98 before being eliminated by
Croatia in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Beckenbauer believed, "the others have learned from us and have now
rushed by. The others are better on the ball, ours aren't able to
play." He said, too: "the Germans have lost their supremacy. We did
not see the signs, we were too complacent."
</P>
<P>
The main problem was in bringing on young talent, according to
Beckenbauer. He rejected also the argument that average foreign
players were blocking the progress of good young players.
</P>
<P>
"Our junior players only have themselves to blame. These foreigners
are only playing because our young players are too weak. The mistakes
are happening in youth team training," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
