<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Butler Says not to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. chief weapons
inspector Richard Butler said on Monday that he would not resign
despite criticism.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason for me to do that," he told NBC's "Today,s
Show" in a interview. "The very idea that my presence in this job
can be used as a diversion from Iraq's failure to give us the
information we need... that somehow this comes down to one
individual, I'm sorry that is such a diversionary tactic and there
would be no reason to resign in the face of that."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has accused Butler of being used as a pawn by the United
States and Britain, who launched four-day bombing campaign against
Iraq last week after they were informed in advance of the report
that Butler would submitted to the Security Council about Iraq's
non-cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Butler maintained that his report to the Security Council was
his and his alone.
</P>
<P>
"I could take you through site by site and I can show you that
in every case there was a disarmament justification for going to
that site. They were my choices. They were based on facts. I did
not discuss them with the United States or anybody else," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
