<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Combat Land Degradation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Africa is losing about nine
billion U.S. Dollars every year as a result of land degradation
which has affected the continent.
</P>
<P>
Alfeyo Hambayi, Zambian Minister of Environment and Natural
Resources, made the remarks here Monday when he opened the first
national action program for combating desertification.
</P>
<P>
In his speech read by Deputy Minister Gibson Nkausu, Hambayi
said losing such amount of money is not healthy for African
economies.
</P>
<P>
He also stated that the Zambian government greatly concerned
about the issue of land degradation caused by inappropriate
agricultural practices.
</P>
<P>
The minister cited poverty, soil erosion and inappropriate
agricultural practices as the factors which have made African
land lose its productivity.
</P>
<P>
He called for concerted efforts especially made by local
community to help maintain the productivity of the land.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Olubanke King Akerele, the United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) country representative, said Africa and Asia
account for more than two-thirds of land degradation in the world
and this has led to increased poverty in most countries.
</P>
<P>
The world is losing about 42 billion Dollars in income every
year as a result of land degradation.
</P>
<P>
She called for the international community to be actively
involved in combating land degradation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
