<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy not to Grant Political Asylum to PKK Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Italy would not grant political
asylum to the Turkish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan and may try him
in Europe or expel him to a third country, Italian Industry
Minister Pierluigi Bersani reiterated here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bersani, who arrived here Monday morning made the remarks after
meeting with his Turkish counterpart Yalim Erez.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish-Italian political and economic ties soured after
Italy rejected a Turkish warrant for the extradition of Abdullah
Ocalan, leader of Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK),
who was detained by the Italian police when he arrived in Rome
from Moscow on November 12.
</P>
<P>
Turkey businesses have imposed an unofficial embargo on Italian
goods, which has caused the Italian companies to lose an estimated
200 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We have received letters from hundreds of Italian companies
that they were in trouble," Bersani said. "Our aim is to solve
this problem within the limits of the Italian Laws while
considering the feelings of the Turkish people," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Italian minister expressed the hope that his meeting with
Erez would help remove the obstacles that have hindered bilateral
economic relations.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish government has made no decision to boycott Italian
goods although we have the right to do so in government
procurements," Erez said. "On the contrary, we want to boost our
economic ties with Italy."
</P>
<P>
Ocalan, who leads the PKK fighting a 14-year-old separatist war
in southeastern Turkey, was forced to leave Syria where he had
been stayed for years. Turkey was on the verge of a war with Syria
in October for Syrian support to and shelter the PKK leaders.
</P>
<P>
Italy is Turkey's second largest trading partner in Europe and
Turkey is eager to join in the European Union (EU). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Welcomes Yemen's Call for Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) welcomes an
appeal by Yemen to hold an Arab summit to examine the current Arab
situation, said Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid Monday.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh is consulting with other
Arab leaders on the proposal, Abdel-Meguid told a press conference
after meeting with Arab countries' representatives to the league.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the Cairo-based league on Sunday, Yemen asked
AL to call an emergency Arab summit to review the situation in the
Arab world, especially after the U.S.-British air strikes against
Iraq since Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The last Arab summit was held in June 1996 in Cairo, one month
after hardline Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took
office, to discuss the challenges that the Arab world was facing.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Algeria have expressed support for holding the
proposed Arab summit.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid urged the United Nations Security Council to play
a decisive role in dealing with the Iraqi issue and live up to its
responsibilities rather than leave the field open to the United
States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have turned a deaf ear to the Arab cries
of anger and resentment. Many people in the Arab countries
denounced as unacceptable the U.S.- British aggression against
Iraq and the brutal killings of Iraqi people, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
