<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Stage Steady Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON December 21 (Xinhua) - The major European stock markets
staged steady gains Monday with the dollar holding its ground and
shares surging in light year-end trade.
</P>
<P>
The markets were boosted by a bullish start on a Wall Street
apparently confident of President Clinton's political survival.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 Index of leading shares started off in
positive territory and surged ahead throughout the day to close at
5875, up 134.6 on the day.
</P>
<P>
Germany's blue-chip Xetra Dax index rose over 3 percent as
traders said Wall Street's ability to shrug off the US president's
impeachment augured well for German shares.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax index closed up 159.96 at 4826.70. The Dow's 1.7
percent surge and the dollar's bounce back above DM1.67 helped
cement the positive tone.
</P>
<P>
French stocks also soared in thin volume, riding the wave of
enthusiasm which started in the US. The Cac 40 index closed up
111.52 points at 3803.41.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the year-end rally came amid a belief on Wall
Street that the Senate will not convict Clinton, whose approval
rating remains high in public opinion polls. 
</P>
