<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Minister Puts Off Visit to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Minister of Energy and
Water Hani Mulki has decided to put off his visit to Iraq at the
request of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The postponement of the visit, slated for December 22, was the
result of the U.S and British air strikes on Iraq last week, Mulki
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Mulki said the attacks, growing out of disputes between the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) and Baghdad, have complicated the
circumstances surrounding the annual meeting between Jordanian and
Iraqi ministers on Iraq's oil supply to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched four successive nights of air
strikes on Iraq with the declared aim to destroy Iraq's military
capabilities and to avenge its defiance of UNSCOM, which is
authorized to monitor Iraq's disarming of weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The minister said oil supply from Iraq to Jordan was unaffected
and actually more oil was shipped.
</P>
<P>
He said Jordan received 117,000 tonnes of oil from Iraq on
December 18 when the bombardment was under way, as against the
usual average 105,000 tonnes a day.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that the kingdom's strategic stock of oil
and oil products could be used for one month.
</P>
<P>
After the Gulf War ended in 1991, sparked by Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait in 1990, Jordan imported 75,000 barrels of crude oil
everyday from Iraq with the consent of the U.N., which imposed
sanctions on Iraq eight years ago, but has allowed Iraq to export
a limited amount of oil since 1996 to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 percent of Iraqi crude oil was granted to Jordan, and
50 percent was bartered with food, cooking oil, medicine and other
goods at discounted prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis:  UN Inspectors Unlikely to Return to Iraq Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- As the United States
and Britain announced the end of their military Strikes against
Iraq on December 19, the question on when the United Nations arms
inspectors would return to Iraq and resume their work has become a
hot topic here at the headquarters of the United Nations. Signs
have shown that there is very little possibility that the UN arms
inspectors could go back to Iraq in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, after hit by the four-day long U.S. military actions, has
reiterated on many occasions that it would not allow U.N.
inspectors to come back until the U.N. sanctions gets lifted.
</P>
<P>
Iraq held that it has cooperated fully with the United Nations
and has destroyed all its weapons of mass destruction in
accordance with relevant U.N. resolutions, and the eight-year
sanctions should have been lifted.
</P>
<P>
Iraq argued that the sanctions have been kept in place for so
long because chief U.N. weapons inspector Richard Butler, who is
accused by Iraq of coordinating with the U.S. Administration's
policies against Iraq, has blocking the process by drawing
negative reports on Iraq's efforts in disarmament and cooperation
with the Untied Nations.
</P>
<P>
Butler, Executive Chairman of the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction, and Iraq has been at odds over the weapons
inspections these years, which led to several military
confrontations between Iraq and the United States, and the
U.S.-led military strikes have made it impossible for Iraq to deal
directly with Butler, and it also made it impossible for Iraq to
allow the U.N. weapons inspectors headed by Butler to return.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said Butler, who reported that U.N. did not get full and
unconditional support from Iraq as it promised last week, prompted
the U.S.-led military strikes and he is not welcome to the country
any longer.
</P>
<P>
The frequent looming of crisis between Iraq and Butler has
seized attention of the United Nations Security Council, which has
began to doubt the effectiveness and fairness of UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the International Atomic Energy Agency, UNSCOM
made very little progress in its work after eight years in Iraq,
that is strong criticized by Council members, namely China, Russia
and France.
</P>
<P>
Russia requested the Security Council have a complete review of
the current working mechanism of UNSCOM and Butler be fired, and
France suggested a new institution to replace UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
But the United States and Britain defended Butler and his
UNSCOM as effective and professional. They want to keep Butler in
the post, and they want UNSCOM to return to Iraq to resume its
work.
</P>
<P>
It is widely seen here that the United Nations arms inspectors
would not return to Iraq in the near future amid Iraq's strong
demands and the Council's sharp division on UNSCOM. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
