<HEADLINE> Britain, U.S. Warn of Further Action Against Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Britain and the United
States warned Libya Monday, which is the 10th anniversary of the
1988 Lockerbie bombing, that they could seek additional measures
if it failed by next February to hand over two suspects in the
case for trial.
</P>
<P>
In statements to the Security Council, which held closed-door
consultations Monday morning, the British and U.S. envoys both
said that they are running out their patience.
</P>
<P>
Libya accepted in August a Washington-London proposal to try
the two Libyans before a Scottish court in the Netherlands. The
two suspects were accused of planting a bomb aboard the American
airliner which later exploded over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing
270 people.
</P>
<P>
At issue is the dispute on the place where the two, if
convicted, should serve their sentences. Libya has been demanding
that they, if found guilty, should not serve their sentences in
Scotland, as proposed by Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Our patience is not unlimited," said Jeremy Greenstock, the
British permanent representative to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"In February, the Security Council will hold its regularly
scheduled review of Libyan sanctions," Peter Burleigh, charge
d'affaires of the U.S. Mission to the United Nations, said.
</P>
<P>
"If by that time, the government of Libya has not handed over
the suspects for trial before a Scottish court in the Netherlands,
we will seek additional measures to compel compliance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said he is
still hopeful to get a positive response from the Libyan
government on the Lockerbie issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
