<HEADLINE> World's First Surviving Octuplets Remain in Critical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The world's first
octuplets to be born alive remain in critical condition in a
hospital in Houston, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Texas Children's Hospital said Monday that the first baby was
born 12 days ago at a local hospital specialized in high risk
pregnancies and multiple births, and then transferred to the
Children's. The other seven babies were born on Sunday, December
20.
</P>
<P>
The parents are American citizens originally from Nigeria, said
the hospital, adding that the babies are expected to be
hospitalized at Texas Children's for at least two months before
being well enough to go home. The mother had taken fertility drugs
and had been told to expect multiple births.
</P>
<P>
According to the hospital, the seven babies born Sunday were 13
weeks premature and delivered by Cesarean section. The baby born
on December 8 was 15 weeks premature and delivered vaginally.
</P>
<P>
Still unnamed, the six baby girls and two boys have their
birthweights ranging between 320 and 810 grams. The biggest is a
boy, the seventh baby, and the smallest, a girl, both born on
Sunday. The eldest baby, a girl with the birthweight of 690 grams,
is now off the ventilator. The other seven babies are all
breathing with the assistance of ventilators, the hospital said.
</P>
</TEXT>
