<HEADLINE> Leading Businessman Kidnapped in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A leading businessman was
kidnapped in the breakaway republic of Chechnya Monday, Interfax
reported.
</P>
<P>
Salambek Khadzhiyev, head of the Chechengazprom Gas Department,
was captured by a group of armed persons wearing camouflage, the
Chechen Shariah Security Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The kidnapping might have been committed to force gas workers
to begin protesting and cut off gas supplies to the population,
thus triggering social unrest, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred Chechengazprom employees held a rally Monday
evening to demand the release of Khadzhiye.
</P>
<P>
Another motive might be to seek a ransom, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The kidnapping came just after the Chechen authorities decided
to halt operations against illegal armed gangs at the start of
Ramadan, which started Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, Shariah State Security Minister Nasrudi Bazhiyev said
that "if armed groups show signs of activity, operations will be
resumed to the former scale without warning."
</P>
<P>
The breakaway republic has been plagued by abductions in recent
years. The victims included federal government officials, ordinary
residents and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Three Britons and a New Zealander, abducted in October, were
found beheaded on December 8, the first killing of foreign
hostages in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo said in
November that some 700 people were being kept hostage in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Organized criminal groups have distributed profitable
operations, some doing kidnapping, others whisking hostages away
and still others "providing maintenance, medical service and
food," Rushailo said. 
</P>
