<HEADLINE> Food Supply in Africa to Improve: UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Food supply in Africa is
expected to improve next year, according to a report of the United
Nations Food and Agriculture Organization released Monday in
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Above average to record harvests were anticipated in western Africa
and a satisfactory amount of food production was expected in eastern
Africa, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But 13 countries were expected to have severe food shortages, with
Somalia to be the worst hit. Last year, the number of such countries
were 20.
</P>
<P>
Mwita Rukandema, who launched the U.N. report, said a major food
crisis was developing in Somalia, with malnutrition cases, already
high, continuing to rise.
</P>
<P>
The report said: "Recent estimates put the number of people facing
food shortages (in Somalia) at 700,000, and those most at risk at
300,000."
</P>
<P>
Rukandema called on world countries to focus attention on the country.
</P>
<P>
Somalia's food crisis was caused by five consecutive bad harvests.
</P>
<P>
The strife-torn Democratic Republic of the Congo and Angola will
also have food problems, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
