<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Deputy PM on U.S.-British Strikes, Fate of UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 21, (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz said Monday that the U.S-British air strikes against
Iraq killed 62 soliders and wounded 180 others.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference on Monday evening that U.S
President Bill Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair
boosted their military achievements, disinformed their people and
the world in order to justify their aggression.
</P>
<P>
He said the serious damage was in civilian sites, however he
did not give the exact figure of civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's U.N. Ambassador Nizar Hamdoon had said over the weekend
that thousands of people were killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. and Britain targeted industrial sites,
government and party buildings, schools, communications centers,
radio and TV stations, hospitals and private houses.
</P>
<P>
Iraq strongly believes that the U.S. and Britain have only
suspended the aggression but not ended it.
</P>
<P>
"The aggression has not stopped, it is continuing against
Iraq, " and it may resume after the holy month of Ramadan, said
the minister.
</P>
<P>
"The question is not Ramadan, they finished a limited amount
of missiles. It was part of the tactics that they suspended their
aggression," he added.
</P>
<P>
Aziz stressed that Iraq will "never accept any conditions made
by Clinton or Blair. Iraq refuses all these conditions totally
and strongly."
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on Iraq's relations with the U.N., Aziz
said it was not Iraq but the U.S. and Britain that damaged the
U.N. itself.
</P>
<P>
"They damaged the power and the mandate of the U.N. Security
Council," he said, adding "they did not act according to
international law".
</P>
<P>
"It is their responsibility to rebuild their relations with
the international community and the U.N. Security Council," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S.-British aggression should be the main focus in
the discussions of the UN Security Council and the embargo imposed
on Iraq should be lifted.
</P>
<P>
On the fate of the U.N. Special Commission for disarming Iraq
(UNSCOM), Aziz said "the moment America and Britain launched
missiles against Iraq, they killed UNSCOM. So UNSCOM is their
casualty, not ours."
</P>
<P>
"After the comprehensive and severe aggression in 1991,
thousands of interviews, thousands of inspections, the imposition
of no-fly zones, there came the 'Operation Desert Fox'. So how
the U.S. and Britain expect to resume weapons inspections?" he
asked.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said "the aggressors wanted to change the government of
Iraq. How can they do this? It is a free and independent
government. They thought foolishly when they sent missiles,
thinking Iraqis will uprise against the leadership, these are
Rambo-like fantasies." 
</P>
</TEXT>
