<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Students to Re-sit for Tests After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian
government has set January 13-17 next year for students to re-sit
for the Form Four nationwide examinations which were suspended
last month following leakages of test papers.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued Monday in Dar es Salaam by the
Tanzania Information Services, the National Examination Council
is in final preparations for the exercise which will cost the
government about 800 million Shillings (about 1.2 million U.S.
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The statement said the Form Four examination which started on
November 3 were nullified by the government on November 6
following leakages of the examination papers in 12 regions.
</P>
<P>
This time, the statement said, the government and its
instruments will be very careful in administering the
examinations.
</P>
<P>
It also warned anybody who tries to involve themselves in
examination leakage and cheating will be severely punished.
</P>
<P>
In a parliamentary session last month, the Act No.3 of the
National Security of 1970 was amended and the Section of National
Examinations was added, said the statement, adding that any
person who are found guilty of cheating in the examinations will
face a maximum of 20 years of imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Minister of Education and Culture Juma Kapuya told
reporters that this was the first time the government has
disregarded and suspended a nationwide examination.
</P>
<P>
He said the syndicate originated in Rukwa Region in the
southwest. Unknown people broke into an office where the
examination papers were kept under custody at Rukwa High School.
They made away with history, geography, Kiswahili, English,
physics, chemistry, biology, basic mathematics, commerce and
book-keeping papers.
</P>
<P>
After stealing the papers, the culprits faxed them to the
other members of the syndicate and circulated them widely,
according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
The police have held a dozen people in connection with the
incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly Tanzanians Fall Victims to Witch-Hunting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of elderly
people in several Lake Victoria regions in Tanzania have fallen
victims to witch-hunting, the Tanzania Media Women's Association
(TAMWA) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report by the Ministry of Home Affairs, Pius Wanzala,
a TAMWA program officer, said more than 1,000 people nationwide
were killed on allegations of witchcraft from 1994 to September
this year.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the report said, 7,727 people were killed
in all kinds of incidents across the country, 1,233 of which were
related to witch-hunting. Among the witch-hunting cases, 400
took place in the Shinyanga Region, with 90 percent of the dead
being elderly women.
</P>
<P>
Wanzala said many people would kill innocent elderly people
out of fear that they are witches who may threaten their lives
with super nature power, especially when people are ill.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to people in the region to abandon superstitious
ideas and stop indiscriminate killings, which are against human
rights and Tanzanian laws. The officer also called for improved
medical care and education services in rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
