<HEADLINE> Britain Says "Desert Fox" Hit Hard at Iraq's Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Britain will produce evidence
over the next few days to show that the four-night-long air
strikes had hit hard at Iraq's military capability.
</P>
<P>
"We know that we have done considerable damage to the war
machine of Iraq...in the next few days evidence will be brought
forward from the battle damage assessments to show that is
absolutely correct," British Defense Secretary George Robertson
told a news conference on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Robertson said his ministry was scheduled to hold a further
news conference on Tuesday to provide further evidence.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials and British military commanders would
show that "while life appears to be going around as normal
inside Iraq, inside the military structures, there has been
immense damage and the impact has been very considerable
indeed."
</P>
<P>
Robertson was speaking alongside German Defense Minister
Rudolph Scharping during a break in meetings during Scharping's
first visit to London since taking office two months ago.
</P>
<P>
He also denied that Britain and the United States were
diplomatically isolated in their stance, saying that a meeting of
NATO defence ministers last week had been unanimous that "it was
necessary, albeit regrettable, to act militarily".
</P>
<P>
"There will be some debates about the political strategy in the
future...but I am sure we will find a common one," he added.
</P>
