<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Foreign RMB Loan for Shanghai Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The first ever mostly foreign
funded loan in China's own currency has been made to the Shanghai
Rubber Company, the country's largest tyre manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
The 80 million yuan (about U.S. 10 million dollars) loan was
organized by the British Standard Chartered Bank's Shanghai branch
working with a foreign banking syndicate.
</P>
<P>
The one-year loan, made in the yuan, follows China's central
bank's recent decision to allow Chinese and foreign banks to work
together in offering loans in the local currency.
</P>
<P>
The banks involved are the Banque de I'industrine et de Suez,
Shanghai-Paris International Bank along with three Chinese banks.
</P>
<P>
The Standard Chartered Bank, the oldest foreign bank in China,
which began operations in 1858, was among the first group of
foreign banks to win approval last year from the People's Bank of
China to handle RMB businesses.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 the Shanghai Rubber Company realized sales revenue of
over 4.3 billion yuan (about 530 million US dollars)). 
</P>
</TEXT>
