<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Gulf States, Iran Boost Ties in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The year 1998 witnessed a
big boost in the relations between Iran and the members of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC). The two sides have been in discord
for nealy two decades.
</P>
<P>
A series of exchanges of visits and talks, which took place
mainly on the Saudi Arabia-Iran and Kuwait-Iran tracks,
characterize the process of rapproachement between the two sides
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance set up in
1981, groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the
United Arab Emirates (UAE), most of which are all oil-rich
countries.
</P>
<P>
Of all those visits, the trip to Saudi Arabia by former Iranian
president Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani last February arrested general
attention in the region. He is the highest ranking Iranian
official who has visited one of the GCC states since Iran's 1979
Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
During his trip to Saudi Arabia, Rafsanjani, who still remains
influential as a top advisor to Iran's Supreme Leader Ayatollah
Seyyed Ali Husseini Khamenei, held talks with Saudi officials on
ways of improving bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The former Iranian president voiced regret over the past
animosity between the two countries, saying "it's a pity that we
didn't have cooperation with Saudi Arabia all these years".
</P>
<P>
Both Iran and Saudi Arabia expressed the hope that they should
open a new chapter in their relations since the two countries play
important roles in the Islamic world, the Gulf region in
particular.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two giants in the Gulf region warmed up
following the election of President Mohammad Khatami last May, who
advocated friendly and peaceful co-existence among regional
countries.
</P>
<P>
Regarding his tour as "one of the most successful foreign
trips by our officials", Rafsanjani said that his visit "melted a
mountain of ice" between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani also tried to coordinate stances with Riyadh, the
Gulf heavyweight, over the world oil price crisis.
</P>
<P>
Differences remained between Iran and the GCC members,
especially Saudi Arabia on how to deal with the oil price crisis,
with Iran favoring additional output reductions while Saudi Arabia
calling for an extension of previous cuts until the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
But the crisis, which affected the economies of both Iran and
Saudi Arabia, forced the two sides, whose proven crude reserves
account for about 36 percent of the world's total, to narrow their
differences and come out with a unified stance.
</P>
<P>
The six GCC countries produce nearly 13.5 million barrels of
oil each day, or one fifth of the world's total. Their oil
reserves, which are estimated at 465 billion barrels, account for
45 percent of the total global oil resources.
</P>
<P>
The GCC members, whose economy depends heavily on oil earnings,
have suffered a hard hit in the current oil price slump resulting
from oversupply and flagging demand.
</P>
<P>
The oil price in January futures contracts for Brent crude -- a
widely watched benchmark -- fell to a record low of 9.92
U.S. dollars a barrel in London. Brent was selling for around 20
dollars a barrel as recently as 1997.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani's tour was followed by a brief visit on March 14 to
Riyadh by Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi, who went to
Saudi Arabia for three more times later in the year.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi delivered to Saudi leaders messages from Iranian
President Khatami each time he visited the kingdom. Khatami
expressed in his letters Iran's desire to enhance mutual
understanding and strengthen coordination in a bid to shore up the
world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
On May 26, Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Saud Al-Faisal paid a
three-day visit to Iran, during which he held talks with Iranian
President Khatami.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Khatami praised the improving relations
between Tehran and Riyadh, saying that the ties would be
beneficial for the whole Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure this new trend which has started in the ties between
our two countries will have extraordinary results for the Islamic
world and bilateral ties," Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
Saud, for his part, expressed appreciation for Khatami's
foreign policy oriented toward establishing better ties with
Iran's Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"You have adopted a correct policy, and hence for this reason
your brothers in Saudi Arabia are extending their hands towards
you, and openly welcome your position on regional issues," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi foreign minister also signed during his visit with
his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi a memorandum of
understanding over future cooperation in all fields.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the Gulf Arab nations and Iran have been
tense until recently, as Iran accused the GCC states of allowing
western presence in the region, while the GCC states kept Tehran
at a distance for its export of the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
But the ice began to thaw in the past year after Khatami, a
political moderate, was elected as the country's president by a
landslide in May.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, with unprecedented popular support, held out the olive
branch to the rest of the world. He launched a charm offensive in
the Gulf region and gave his foreign policy the priority to the
improvement of relations between Iran and its Gulf Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
On the Iran-Kuwait track, Iranian Majlis (parliament) Speaker
Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri arrived in Kuwait on April 27 on an
official visit.
</P>
<P>
As a goodwill gesture, Nouri assured Kuwait that Iran has "no
relations whatsoever with Iraq," adding that its relations with
Iraq did not go beyond the necessary follow-up concerning
U.N. Security Council resolutions related to the 1980-1988
Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day stay in Kuwait, the Iranian parliament
speaker also stressed the importance of exchange visits by
Iranian high-level officials and the Gulf Arab countries as "a
chance to open dialogue that would help to remove the existing
mistrust."
</P>
<P>
Analysts say a desperate need for regional security and
stability may have prompted the rapprochement process between
Iran and the GCC states.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of 1980s, peoples in the Gulf region have
been suffering from wars and instability.
</P>
<P>
The eight-year-long Iran-Iraq war in 1980-1988 proved that both
sides were losers in terms of political and economic benefits, not
to mention the heavy costs resulting from the war itself.
</P>
<P>
On June 9, Kuwaiti Interior Minister Sheikh Mohammad Khaled
Al-Hamad Al-Sabah arrived in Tehran on a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said in his meeting with the Kuwaiti minister that
"today before any other time, the region is in need of security
and stability, through cooperation and initiatives taken by all
the regional countries. We must eliminate factors leading to
tension and instability."
</P>
<P>
He said that the trip would be another step in expanding mutual
understanding which will in turn lead to further cooperation in
political, economic and security issues.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Iran have begun talks with UAE on a
thorny dispute over three Gulf islands, namely, Abu Musa and
Greater and Lesser Tunbs.
</P>
<P>
The islands are strategically located on the edge of the Strait
of Hormuz, which as the only way to the Gulf, much of the world's
oil ships have to pass through.
</P>
<P>
Iran seized the islands in 1971 as Britain wound up its
colonial rule in the region. Tehran later agreed to share
sovereignty over Abu Musa, the largest of the islands, with
Sharjah, one of seven emirates federated in the UAE.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic relations between Tehran and Abu Dhabi were lowered
to the level of charge d'affaires in 1992 after the UAE lodged a
protest to Iran's full control on the islands of Abu Musa, the
Greater and Lesser Tunbs, over which both sides claimed full
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The two Tunbs are uninhabited, but Iran has set up military
bases on them. Abu Musa has a predominantly Persian population.
</P>
<P>
As a positive gesture to resolve the long-standing dispute,
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi flew to Abu Dhabi on May
23, where he held talks with UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan
Al-Nahyan and his UAE counterpart Sheikh Hamdan Bin Zayed
al-Nahyan on the disputed islands.
</P>
<P>
Though no progress emerged from the talks, both sides
"expressed common view in creating an atmosphere of mutual trust
and cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Political analysts in the region held that the momentum of the
GCC-Iran rapprochement will at least continue if not to be
accelerated in the years to come, since both Iran's comprehensive
economic reforms initiated last August and the economic
diversification programs in the GCC states need a stable and
peaceful environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Regrets U.S. Publication of Sanction List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
filed a complaint with the WTO regarding the publication by the
United States of a trade sanction's list on EU exports.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions could eventually cost the EU about 500 million
European Currency Units (ECU) (about 600 million U.S. dollars) in
trade.
</P>
<P>
A written statement issued on Tuesday quoted European
Commission Vice-President Sir Leon Brittan as saying that he
regretted "very much" that the U.S. had gone ahead with publishing
the list of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has regrettably chosen not to take a
multilateral path but rather to embark on unilateral trade
sanctions. These are specifically condemned by the World Trade
Organization (WTO) rules," said Brittan.
</P>
<P>
But the EU still hopes the U.S. will respond to the union's
desire to resolve the trade dispute "lawfully and amicably," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The union would "not like to play the game of sanctions, but
rather play the game according to its rules," a commission
spokesman said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
He said that though the publication of a sanction list was
illegal and arbitrary, the union would not put out a retaliatory
list of its own and would still sort out the issue through the
dispute settlement mechanism within the WTO.
</P>
<P>
The EU submitted their complaint to the Geneva-based WTO
against America's unilateralism on Monday, according to the
spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
