<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Treat Calmly NATO's Expansion: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Defense Minister
Oleksandr Kuzmuk said on Monday that his country would "treat
calmly" the eastward expansion of NATO, stressing that every
independent nation "has the right to determine its position in a
union."
</P>
<P>
Kuzmuk made the remark while attending the Executive Council of
Defense Ministers of the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS) as an observer, reported the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
As the first country to dismantle their nuclear weapons,
Ukraine opposes the deployment of nuclear weapons among NATO's new
members, said Kuzmuk.
</P>
<P>
But Ukraine did not oppose the establishment nor the usage of
NATO military facilities in those countries, for this is "the
internal affairs of every country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary are expected to be
adopted as the first new NATO member states at the NATO summit
scheduled on April next year in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine has not raised the issue of joining NATO, said Kuzmuk,
but it is cooperating with NATO under the special partnership
charter signed by two sides in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
