<HEADLINE> Scientists Find Oldest Whales Fossil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Paleontologists from the
United States and India have discovered in the Himalayan foothills
a fossilized whale's jawbone and teeth.
</P>
<P>
The fossil suggests the newly found whale species, named
Himalayecetus subathuensis, may be about 53.5 million years old,
said scientists from the University of Rookee in India and the
University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
Reporting Monday in the Proceedings of the National Academy of
Sciences, they said the new species is 3.5 million years older
than a species found in Pakistan that had been regarded as the
most ancient whale fossil.
</P>
<P>
The fossils were found in a shallow, oyster-hearing marine
deposit in the vicinity of the Tethys Sea, an early sea once
separating the Indian subcontinent from the rest of Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
