<HEADLINE> UNESCO Gift of Books Welcomed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of China's educational
establishments are to benefit from the donation of sets of the
internationally acclaimed Encyclopaedia Britannica by UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
The company that publishes the comprehensive set, known
colloquially as "the university without walls" has offered UNESCO
one thousand sets of the printed books for distribution throughout
the Asia-Pacific region, valued at 2.8 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony in Beijing's Great Hall of the People today, Mr
Corey McMahon, the managing director of Encyclopaedia Brittanica
(Australia) said that in an era which has so readily embraced
high technology for education, it is humbling to be reminded that
there are still those who have a desperate hunger for education
but do not have access to it through modern technology.
</P>
<P>
He announced that 447 sets of the encyclopaedia would be
distributed throughout China: some 268 copies will go to
Experimental Middle Schools in Beijing, Shanxi and Shaanxi, under
the Secondary School Joint Innovative Project co-sponsored by
UNESCO and China. The remainder will be donated to Normal
Universities at the Education Ministry level and the Provincial
level.
</P>
<P>
Wei Yu, vice-minister and chairperson of the Chinese National
Commission for UNESCO, declared that the ambitious "Education
Action Plan for the 21st Century" formulated recently by the
Chinese government, is designed to accelerate the reform and
development of science and education, thus revitalizing the
country.
</P>
<P>
She said that UNESCO was making its contribution to the
execution of the Plan through such cooperative and beneficial
projects like this.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that next time I visit those schools, I will see that
the encyclopaedias have been read frequently and are not just for
show," stressed Dr Ian Birch, education consultant from the Asian
Center of Education and Innovation for Development(ACEID) under
UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
Then he announced that today's gift was merely the start of an
ongoing project to distribute educational materials throughout
China.
</P>
<P>
"Already I am delighted to tell you that we have agreed to
allocate a further 300 sets of the encyclopaedia along with a
further 166,000 volumes of other reference books and textbooks
with a retail value of 8 million U.S. dollars." he said, adding
that they would be distributed around secondary school and
teaching institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
