<HEADLINE> Ancient Chinese Technology Show Draws Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- An ongoing exhibition of
invaluable gems of Chinese scientific and technological innovation
has proven to be one of the most popular exhibitions ever held by
the Museum of History of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition called "Heavenly Creations -- Gems of Ancient
Chinese Inventions" has attracted a record number of more than
80,000 visitors since it was launched in late September, a
Provisional Urban Council (PUC) spokesman said Tuesday. The
exhibition is to close on January 3.
</P>
<P>
A joint presentation by the National Museum of Chinese History
and the PUC, the exhibition features 250 items of precious relics,
pictures and replicas selected from 19 museums and archeological
research institutes in China.
</P>
<P>
They are grouped under the fields of astronomy, paper making,
printing, the compass, gunpowder, agriculture, textiles, ceramics,
metallurgy and machinery.
</P>
<P>
Highlights of the exhibits include the world's oldest surviving
map on paper, the ingenious water clock, the seismograph invented
by Zhang Heng, the odometer and the south-pointing carriage.
</P>
</TEXT>
