<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Stock Market to Remain Volatile: HKSE Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The high volatility in the
stock market will remain for some time next year, Alec Tsui, chief
executive of the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong, said here Tuesday
at a year-end review press conference.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, Tsui briefed the media on the market
performance, the exchange's achievements in 1998 and plans for the
coming year.
</P>
<P>
As of November 26, 1998, the market value of shares of domestic
listed companies in Hong Kong dropped 18.4 percent compared with
that at the same period last year, Tsui said.
</P>
<P>
As of December 18, 1998, the bench-mark Hang Seng Index (HSI)
went down by 5 percent to 10,226 points from the 10,754 points on
December 18, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The market capitalization decreased 16 percent over the same
period last year. The total turnover and the average daily
turnover in the past 12 months ending December 18 slid by 55
percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong has achieved positive
results in re-organizing the exchange structure, drawing up the
listing rules and policy, strengthening members regulations,
tackling the year 2000 problem and reviewing the compensation
scheme, Tsui said.
</P>
<P>
Looking forward, Tsui said the exchange will make efforts to
restore the market's capital formation capability through raising
market quality, which includes improving market facilities,
strengthening market regulations, increasing market transparency
and improving market efficiency as well as strengthening investor
protection and education.
</P>
<P>
Tsui said the exchange will continue to increase its
competitive edge and is competing vigorously in the highly
competitive international exchange industry. He believes that Hong
Kong will maintain its position as a major international financial
center in the Asia-Pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
