<HEADLINE> Italy to Assist Albania in Curbing Flow of Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Italy will continue to provide
Albania with economic and social assistance to help stop the flow
of refugees from entering Italy, said visiting Italian
Social and Family Affairs Minister Livia Turco on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Italy will not only continue to fund the previously agreed upon
cooperation programs between the two countries, but will also
advise Albania on how to formulate relevant laws and regulations,
Turco told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Italy will initiate 64 social cooperation programs worth 20
billion lira (12.7 million U.S. dollars) with Albania, which will
provide assistance to women, children, juveniles and try to reduce
poverty, she added.
</P>
<P>
During her stay here, Turco met with Albanian President Mexhep
Meidani and Prime Minister Pandeli Majko.
</P>
<P>
Meidani called on the two countries to make joint efforts to
help Albania shake off its economic problems and political
instability.
</P>
<P>
Majko attributed the flow of Albanian illegals across the
border to poverty in their own country. He called for the
earliest implementation of the bilateral cooperation programs. He
also noted that present police measures were not enough.
</P>
<P>
By estimate, about 100,000 Albanian refugees have illegally
entered Italy since 1991. About 51,000 were caught by Italian
police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
