<HEADLINE> Five Rivers in Northern Bangladesh Changing Courses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Five major rivers flowing
through Bangladesh's northern districts are changing their courses
in their land of origin in India, the Associated Press of
Bangladesh (APB) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is due to the commissioning of the Teesta Barrage in India
and unilateral withdrawal of waters, especially during the dry
season, an executive engineer of the Water Development Board was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The rivers are Karotoa, Mahananda, Atrai, Teesta and Dharala
and all the rivers have been also losing their navigability, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Vast lands in the northern region of Bangladesh are facing
desertification as a result of the massive and unilateral
withdrawal of waters by India, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The level of ground water has also gone down because of this,
badly affecting irrigation in the northern region of the country,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
