<HEADLINE> China's Top Lawmaker Urges Study of the Past </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislator Li Peng
today called for improving China's legal system by examining the
country's rich legal heritage stretching back thousands of years
which he insists has a lot to teach today's modern society.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress, the country's highest legislature, made the remarks at
the sixth legal conference sponsored here today by the NPC
Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China has yet to tap its rich lawmaking
heritage and its traditionally efficient, and admired legal
framework. "We should discard the dross and pick up the
essentials," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Li added that perhaps the country could also examine
the useful experience of foreign countries, although with maybe a
critical eye,
</P>
<P>
The chairman described the third plenary session of the 11th
Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party, which was
convened 20 years ago, as a great watershed which helped bring an
end to the country's lawlessness during the " Cultural
Revolution". Li said that it had anchored China, enabling it to
build up a proper legal system.
</P>
<P>
Today's discussion and speech in Beijing are aimed at improving
the legal knowledge of the members of NPC Standing Committee and
to commemorate the 3rd plenum of the 11th Party Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jinfan, a professor with the China University of Law and
Political Science, also gave a lecture on China's legal tradition
attended by staff workers and officials of the NPC Standing
Committee. 
</P>
