<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millions of Sudanese May Face Famine in 1999: UNICEF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- More than four million Sudanese
will continue to live under the threat of famine if peace and
security are not firmly established in the conflict-affected areas
throughout the country, a U.N. organization said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Many people are surviving on the bare minimum and that slim
hope could be shattered in the event their lives are once again
disrupted by turmoil, the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF) said.
</P>
<P>
"Even a few weeks of insecurity, especially in Bahr el Ghazal,
could produce the kind of crisis we confronted earlier this year,"
said Philippe Borel, U.N. coordinator for relief operations in
Sudan. He is also head of Operation Lifeline Sudan (OLS), which
has just published its 1998 Annual Needs Assessment.
</P>
<P>
"It takes years for people to recover once they get caught in a
vicious cycle of desperation such as this," said David Fletcher,
acting country director for Kenya for the World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
Fletcher, who is also deputy coordinator of OLS, said that
hundreds of thousands of families who have lost their homes,
livestock and crops "are still living dangerously on the edge."
</P>
<P>
And that makes a cease-fire essential for averting famine in
1999, said Borel.
</P>
<P>
The OLS annual report cautioned that the situation in the Upper
Nile region, where local populations are still suffering from
interfactional fighting and flooding in 1998, could deteriorate if
insecurity continues to hamper relief efforts or large-scale
population displacement occurs.
</P>
<P>
By late 1998, the report said persistent insecurity, especially
around Leer, and flooding had displaced some 150,000 people,
forced OLS agencies to evacuate, and limited humanitarian services
to some locations.
</P>
<P>
In northern Sudan, the report warned, humanitarian needs could
increase in the Kassala region, where insecurity escalated in 1998
and may continue in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
