<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Indian-Russian Relations and Beyond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov winded up his two-day official visit to India
Tuesday in the context of the United States and British air
strikes against Iraq, which led to the urgent return to Moscow of
Russian foreign and defence ministers from their foreign trips.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Primakov refused to postpone the visit showed
Moscow's opposition to the strikes and sent a signal to Washington
that Russia is against a unipolar world in which the U.S. could
cast itself in the role of a global policeman.
</P>
<P>
"Delhi and Moscow share the concept of a multi-polar world and
the supremacy of the United Nations in resolving international
disputes and this is a good time for them to reiterate their
stand," a Russian foreign ministry source said last week.
</P>
<P>
Despite its very strong opposition to the eastward extension of
NATO, Moscow has avoided frontal confrontation with it by signing
the Russia-NATO Foundation Act on May 27, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that one reason for Primakov's visit to New
Delhi is to exhibit the special relationship between India and
Russia which is right in the midst of negotiations with western
countries for food for its scarcity-hit regions and cities.
</P>
<P>
The agreements signed on Monday between the two countries
included a broad-based defence pact, the Long-term Agreement on
Military-Technical Cooperation up to the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which was based on the existing one that expires
on December 31, 2000, is expected to boost the slumping Russian
defence equipment manufactures.
</P>
<P>
Primakov is the first head of government of the five permanent
members of the United Nations Security Council to visit New Delhi
since India's nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
Russia jointed the international community to condemn the tests
but opposed from the very beginning to impose sanctions by the
United States and other countries on its traditional ally.
</P>
<P>
However, Primakov's request for India to sign the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT), which was reportedly raised during
his talks with Indian Minister for External Affairs Jaswant Singh,
was refused by the Indian side.
</P>
<P>
Singh told Primakov that his country might contemplate to join
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT), "but we will never join
the NPT".
</P>
<P>
The visit by the Russian leader might save New Delhi's face
following the postponement of the much-desired visit by Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, which was originally scheduled for
Communications and a Consular Convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian President: Regional Countries Should </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami said here Tuesday that the regional states should
protect their interest themselves in the region, the Islamic
Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
"If the regional countries stand together, there is no need
for the presence of foreigners," Khatami told visiting Omani
Minister of Commerce and Industry Maqbool Bin Ali Bin Sultan.
</P>
<P>
He said that the recent U.S.-British strikes against Iraq was
a great tragedy for the Iraqi oppressed people and the Islamic
Republic of Iran which as chairman of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference has condemned this aggression.
</P>
<P>
"We have also asked Iraq to act in agreement with
international regulations and the Security Council resolutions, so
as not to give others any excuses since it's the people of Iraq
and the regional states who pay for it," the Iranian president
said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Iran-Oman relations, Khatami said Oman's policy
has pursued cooperation among Muslim states in the region,
tranquility in the region and consolidation of the ties.
</P>
<P>
The Omani minister delivered a message from Sultan Qaboos of
Oman to Khatami.
</P>
<P>
He highlighted the active status of the Iran-Oman joint
economic commission and called for further expansion of ties
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He also voiced his country's readiness to cooperate with
member states of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries for reduction of oil production. 
