<HEADLINE> Philippine Officials Warned Against Accepting Gifts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
warned officials Tuesday against accepting expensive Christmas
gifts, especially if they are apparently meant to influence
official decisions.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here by the presidential office, a
government spokesman said the law allows public servants to
receive only gifts of little monetary value as tokens of the
Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
"There is still the law that we cannot receive gifts. The gifts
that can be accepted are only those worth little monetary value,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the law penalizes both the giver and the receiver, once
the graft-busting office finds them liable for giving and
accepting expensive gifts.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora also said
the law applies also to members of the congress, and he cautioned
them to be wary of what the public may perceive about their
receiving such gifts.
</P>
<P>
"I think congressmen should be very careful about the
perceptions of people. There is a law, the ethical standards law,
so they have to be a little careful about these things," Zamora
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
