<HEADLINE> China Sponsors Development Zone in Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The East African Investment
Ltd., a venture run jointly by China Enterprises Network (CEN)
and the Beijing-based Dahua Electronics Company, has recently
been registered in Nairobi, Xinhua learned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new venture, with its office building along the Ngong Road
in Kenya's capital, plans to build a two-square-kilometer
processing development zone in Nairobi to facilitating Chinese
companies which intend to explore their business in this east
African country, Hou Long, the company's representative, told
Xinhua here.
</P>
<P>
After completion, Hou said, the development zone will be able
to host 30 to 50 Chinese companies for producing and marketing
their products in the zone.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not give the amount of investment required for
the opening up of the development zone.
</P>
<P>
Hou said that the Dahua Electronics and CEN have decided to
set up a computer factory in the zone. With an investment of 20
million U.S. Dollars in the next two years, the factory will have
an annual production capacity of 50,000 computers.
</P>
<P>
Of the factory's production, Hou said, 20 percent of the
products are targeted for local market and the rest will go to
other countries in east and southern Africa including Tanzania
and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The Dahua Electronics Company and the CEN have established a
joint venture, Neo-King Take Ltd. in Nairobi with a Kenyan
company for marketing computer and accessories, and providing
training and relevant services. 
</P>
