<HEADLINE> Iran, Iraq Halt Operations to Find Bodies of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Iraqi stopped the
joint operations for searching remains of soldiers killed in the
1980-88 war following the U.S.-British strikes against Iraq, an
Iranian official announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An official at the committee in charge of searching for those
missing in action (MIAs) said that the joint operations had been
launched in cooperation with Iraqi officials in Shalamcheh border
region of the two countries last year.
</P>
<P>
In order to provide security for the groups searching for the
remains of Iranian soldiers in Iraq, the members of the groups,
with all their equipment, have been pulled back to the Iranian
territory, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the search operation would resume after the
return of normal conditions, final cessation of the U.S.-British
attacks on Iraq and announcement of Iraq's readiness.
</P>
<P>
The two countries swapped remains of 385 Iranians and 447
Iraqis this year as a result of their joint search
operations. 
</P>
