<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Expresses Confidence on Winning Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 22 (Xinhua) -- One day after the Israeli
Knesset (Parliament) passed the first reading of a bill for early
elections, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said on Tuesday that
the public would back his peace policy with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Netanyahu said that "we
will go to the people and the people will give us the support to
achieve peace with security."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also brushed aside a public opinion poll published
on local daily Yediot Aharonot, which suggested that Netanyahu
would be defeated if he competed now with his two major political
rivals separately in general elections.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister predicted that he would draw massive
support from voters who are affiliated with his Likud party.
</P>
<P>
However, Dan Meridor, former finance minister of Netanyahu's
government, announced on Tuesday that he was quitting the Likud
party and entering the race for prime minister himself.
</P>
<P>
Following Monday's vote in the Knesset, Meridor was the first
Likud member to challenge Netanyahu. And this move will weaken
Netanyahu's strength in the elections.
</P>
<P>
During the interview, Netanyahu also reiterated the conditions
to further implement the land-for-peace agreement with the
Palestinians singed in October.
</P>
<P>
He said that the turmoil caused by the pending early elections
have no influence on the fulfillment of the accord.
</P>
<P>
And a statement issued by Netanyahu's office also said on
Tuesday that "Israel will carry out its part in the agreement,
without any relation to the election schedule."
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinian National Authority has rejected the
additional conditions and called on Israel to honor the signed
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The early elections bill must pass two more readings in the
Knesset. But since Netanyahu has said he will not try to block
its passage, the bill will pass finally and early elections are
expected to be held next April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
