<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV/Aids Patients Can Study in S. African Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Pupils and students with
HIV/ Aids may not be prevented from going to university and
school, nor may a teacher be dismissed if he or she contracts the
disease, the South African Education Department said.
</P>
<P>
The Star daily Tuesday quoted a draft policy of the department
published in the latest Government Gazette as saying that there
was an "insignificant risk" of transmission in schools and
institutions.
</P>
<P>
"There are no known cases of HIV transmission in schools or
higher education institutions," it stated.
</P>
<P>
Testing for HIV/Aids is prohibited, and the disease sufferers
may not be compelled to disclose if they have the illness to
authorities. However, "voluntary disclosure should be welcomed,"
the document said.
</P>
<P>
The main aim of the new policy, which has been welcomed in
KwaZulu Natal Province where infection rates are estimated to be
more than 30 percent, is to prevent discrimination against Aids
sufferers, to increase awareness of the disease and to prevent
its spread.
</P>
<P>
"Learners and students with HIV/Aids should lead as full a
life as possible and should not be denied the opportunity to
receive an education," the policy document said.
</P>
<P>
According to the South African Education Department,
scientific evidence suggests that the risk of HIV transmission
during teaching, sports and play activities is insignificant if
ordinary hygiene precautions are adhered to.
</P>
<P>
These precautions include the training of teacher, pupils and
students on how to cope should a situation arise where there is a
risk of transmission.
</P>
<P>
In contact sports, such as rugby, proper wound management in
the case of bleeding should prevent transmission.
</P>
<P>
South Africa makes Aids education compulsory and says that a
continuing HIV/Aids education program must be implemented at all
schools and institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Diamond Sales Slump Affects Botswana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The disappointing
diamond sales by South Africa's diamond giant De Beers in 1998
have pointed to a difficult financial year ahead for neighboring
Botswana, local daily The Citizen reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
De Beers sold raw diamond for 4.64 billion U.S. dollars in
1998, down 200 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Botswna's economy is closely related to its diamond
production. It is the world's largest producer of diamonds by
value and accounts for 33.5 percent of diamonds sold to the
Central Selling Organization (CSO) of De Beers.
</P>
<P>
Botswana's diamond industry is inextricably tied to the CSO.
The country's sales of diamond are all through the CSO. The
stones are mined by Debswana which is a 50 to 50 partnership
between De Beers and the Botswana government.
</P>
<P>
The CSO sales were the lowest for 10 years and lower than
those of the two toughest years for Botswana during the that
period, 1991 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
Botswana's sales to the CSO in the first half of 1998 were
15.6 percent down on 1997 in U.S. Dollar terms, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
