<HEADLINE> Beijing Police Crack Major Foreign Exchange Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Beijing police have recently
exposed a foreign exchange fraud case involving 130 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Police sources in the Chinese capital said the Renfu New
Technology Development Center, a Beijing-based foreign trade
company, had used 284 fake customs documents to buy 130 million US
dollars from banks since September 1997.
</P>
<P>
It sold the hard currencies to some Chinese companies which
requested that the money be remitted directly to their bank
accounts abroad. The deal enabled the center to earn 12 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Such cheating on the foreign exchange, resulting in capital
outflow, constitutes a major crime in China as the country imposes
control over capital accounts.
</P>
<P>
Police have arrested eight people including two bank clerks who
assisted in the fraud, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
