<HEADLINE> 3 Nigerian Parties Get Registration Certificates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Three Nigerian political
parties were Monday granted certificates of full registration by
the Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC), media
reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The certificates were presented by INEC chairman, Justice
Ephraim Akpata in Nigerian capital Abuja to chairmen of the
People's Democratic Party, (PDP), the All People's Party (APP)
and the Alliance for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
The final registration of the three parties were announced by
INEC last Monday, which will enable the parties to participate in
remaining elections under the military government's transition to
civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
The INEC had earlier approved the provisional registration of
nine parties, but it ruled that only those that scored five
percent of the total votes cast in each of at least 24 states out
of a total of 36 states and the Federal Capital Territory (FCT)
in the local elections would be given formal registration.
</P>
<P>
According to INEC figures, the PDP won five percent and above
of the total votes in 36 states and FCT with 459 chairmanship
positions and 4,650 councillorship seats in the December 5 local
elections.
</P>
<P>
The APP scored five percent votes and above in 36 states
including FCT with 188 chairmanship position and 2,589
councillorship seats.
</P>
<P>
AD scored five percent and above of total votes cast in 14
states including the Federal Capital Territory (FCT) and won 100
chairmanship positions and 1,071 councillorship seats, but INEC
rules allow it to be registered as the party that is nearest to
the standard out of the remaining seven parties that failed the
standard.
</P>
<P>
According to the transition timetable, Nigeria would hold the
state governors and legislators elections in January and the
presidential election in February, while the civilian president
would be sworn in in May 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
