<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian Ambassador to the
United States Yuri Vorontsov, who was recalled for consultations
in protest against U.S. airstrikes on Iraq, will return to
Washington Wednesday, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the consultations became necessary due to
the strikes "which, the Russian leadership believes, have created a
rather serious situation complicating the work of the United
Nations, including in the sphere of the nonproliferation of
nuclear weapons."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military action has also affected Russian-U.S.
cooperation, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"The complication of Russian-U.S. relations was not our
choice," he said. "Russia has stood and is standing for consistent
development of relations between Moscow and Washington, which
conforms to the interests of our countries and international
stability."
</P>
<P>
"Much will depend on U.S. policy and on whether the United
States is going to take favorable steps," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also announced that U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright would visit Moscow in the second half of next
January.
</P>
<P>
He said Moscow hopes that Albright's visit would help overcome
"the negative consequences of the U.S. use of force against Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Now that the United States has stopped using force against Iraq
which Russia insists on, the process of settling the Iraq crisis
by political means should be restored fully and the key part of
the U.N. Security Council in this process should be reinstated, he
said
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the spokesman said that consultations
with the Russian Ambassador to Britain Yuri Fokin was continuing
and that Fokin would return to London after the consultations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
