<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Machinery and Manufacturing Sector on a Roll in 1999: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) --China's manufacturing and
machinery industry has picked up since the third quarter of this
year with official statistics showing an increase of 3.8 percent
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
This is actually 1.7 percentage points higher than the growth
level in the first eight months of this year and experts predict
it will continue its upward momentum in 1999.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that demand for building materials will become
a hot spot as the real estate market continues its boom and China
will increase even further the investment in infrastructure
construction.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, timber imports will further increase in 1999 since
the Chinese Government decided to stop logging in natural forests
this year, resulting in a drop in the domestic timber output.
</P>
<P>
And there will still be a domestic oversupply of finished steel
which has also been hit by cheaper imports from Russia and the
Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
However, economic analysts agree that it will be necessary to
control the import volume and crack down on smuggling to stimulate
domestic demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
