<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen communities in Bayelsa
State, southeast Nigeria, have given Texaco Overseas Nigeria
Petroleum Company a seven-day ultimatum to pay 23 million U.S.
Dollars compensation for an oil spillage.
</P>
<P>
If Texaco Nigeria fails to pay the compensation, it will risk
its platform being taken over by youths, said a letter dated
December 20, which was sent Monday to the managing director of
the company.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by This Day newspaper Tuesday, the
letter claimed that since the spillage occurred on July 12 this
year, Taxaco Nigeria had refused to have dialog with the affected
communities.
</P>
<P>
Having failed to resolve the five-month-old spillage dispute
through all measures of dialog, the letter said, "the community
elders have directed the youths to be prepared to do a show down
with your firm since that is the only language you understand."
