<HEADLINE> 70 Rebels Killed in Clashes in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Some 70 rebels were killed
Saturday in clashes between the rebels and pro-government forces
in Sierra Leone's eastern diamond-rich region of Naibun, New
Nigerian Tuesday quoted a security source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that the pro-government forces of Kamajors,
a traditional hunting society, captured six villages in Pendembu
near the Liberian border and seized arms and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
The West African peace-keeping force of ECOMOG authorized to
be in charge of security in the country confirmed the capture of
the diamond town of Koidu Saturday by rebels after a two-day
battle last week with Kamajors.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted ECOMOG spokesman Colonel Jimoh Okunlola as
saying that after heavy fighting, "we had to withdraw from Koidu
to re-group and relaunch further attacks on rebel positions."
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, ECOMOG helicopters airlifted dozens of wounded
civilians to the capital Freetown from Koidu, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG announced Sunday an extended night curfew in Freetown,
saying that all residents in Freetown would be required to be
behind closed doors from 10 p.m. until 6:30 a.m. instead of the
previous midnight to 6:00 a.m. curfew.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops have stepped up patrol of beaches and suburbs of
the capital for fear of a new rebel advance toward Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Following the capture of Koidu by rebels, the Liberian
government closed on Sunday its borders with Sierra Leone to
prevent the violence in its neighboring country from spilling
over. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
