<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Trade Development Council Plans Budget to Boost Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Trade Development
Council (TDC) has planned a one-billion-HK-dollar (128.2 million
U.S. dollars) budget to help Hong Kong companies market their
products and services worldwide next year, the Council's Executive
Director Michael Sze announced here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite heavy cuts to its income from trade declaration charges
due to rate reduction and trade downturn, the TDC is determined to
provide more promotional opportunities and better services to
business. "In the tough times, it is particularly necessary for
TDC to do more to help Hong Kong companies, especially small and
medium-sized enterprises, compete in overseas markets," Sze said
at a year-ending briefing.
</P>
<P>
TDC is now going through a vigorous exercise to examine ways to
cut internal costs, increase the value of every dollar spent on
promotion and to add more value to the programs and services
provided. Among various measures to take is that TDC executives
eligible for traveling on business class flights will now switch
to economic class, except for inter-continental business trips.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will face a tough challenge concerning trade in the
coming year, the TDC predicted. Hong Kong's merchandise exports
are forecast to contract again next year, but more modestly. Total
exports are likely to drop five percent, with domestic exports
likely falling by seven percent and re-exports by five percent.
These estimated figures for the whole of this year are minus eight
percent, minus 11 percent and minus eight percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Imports, which are linked to re-export performance and domestic
demand, are forecast to fall by five percent, against the 1998
figure of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
But Hong Kong's service exports, by contrast, are expected to
register a modest gain next year, against a very low base this
year.
</P>
<P>
Prospects for Hong Kong's exports will continue to be
overshadowed by the Asian financial turmoil. There are signs of
improving macroeconomic fundamentals in the region. But the
lingering effects of the economic crisis are unlikely to subside
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The global economic growth is going to slow down and both
China's mainland and Hong Kong SAR are to face greater challenges
next year, Edward Leung, TDC's Chief Economist predicted. "But
the situation will improve in 2000," he said at the briefing on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
With more productivity being switched to China's mainland, Hong
Kong's GDP is expected to drop while GNP is to improve, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
