<HEADLINE> South China's Guangzhou City to Open Wider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, will further emancipate the mind and
open wider to the outside world, Mayor Lin Shusen said today.
</P>
<P>
While addressing a meeting citing Guangzhou's outstanding
achievements in overseas-financed enterprises, Lin said his city
will increase the number of industries making use of overseas
investment, and advance the opening up of the service trades.
</P>
<P>
Greater efforts should be made to attract more overseas funds
to the city's high-tech sector, said the mayor, while urging that
more attention be paid to fighting hidden risks from foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
The mayor also pledged to try all possible means to increase
exports, go all out to improve the investment environment in
Guangzhou, and increase economic and technological cooperation
between Guangzhou and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A total of 59 overseas-backed enterprises were cited at today's
meeting for good performances in both investment and export,
according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou now has 8,544 overseas-financed enterprises. By
November this year, the actual paid-in volume of overseas
investment into the city had hit 16.61 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, overseas-backed enterprises accounted for about 42
percent of Guangzhou's total industrial output value, shipped 60.7
percent of the city's total exports, and generated 30 percent of
the city's gross tax revenues, sources said.  
</P>
