<HEADLINE> Russian Prime Minister Ends Visit to India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov left here for home Tuesday afternoon following his 44-hour
official visit to india in an effort to promote and strengthen the
bilateral relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ministers of the two sides signed seven agreements Monday evening
after wide-ranging talks between Primakov and Indian Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
The Long-Term Agreement on Military-Technical Cooperation upto
to the year 2010, along with the other six agreements on various
issues, highlighted Primakov's visit.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Prime Minister told reporters that Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, who cancelled his planned visit to New
Delhi in December, would visit the country sometimes next year.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said that he discussed with his Indian counterpart
about wide-ranging issues including bilateral, regional and
international relations.
</P>
<P>
But Primakov's request for India to sign the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) was refused during his separate
talks with Indian Minister for External Affairs Jaswant Singh.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Prime Minister said that the agreements signed on
Monday would give a fresh impetus to close and long-term bilateral
ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the press on the talks between officials of the two
governments, an Indian official said that both sides evinced keen
interest in bolstering cooperation in the fields of steel, coal,
petroleum, civil aviation, communications, science and technology
and transport.
</P>
<P>
In his talks with Indian Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha on
Monday, the visiting Russian Trade Minister G, V. Gabuniya asked
India to ease trade restrictions to further improve the bilateral
trade relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
