<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT -- The Kuwaiti government has embarked on cutting
expenditures to the tune of 14.47 billion U.S. dollars in its
1998/1999 budger which has been put in force in July, Tuesday's
Egyptian daily Alam Al Yom reported.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the Kuwaiti council of
ministers, following its weekly meeting, the anticipated net
deficit in the current budget stands at 6.38 billion dollars, the
overall deficit amounts to 7.19 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A recent report by the Arab Organization for
Industrial and Mineral Development said that the number of small
and medium industrial establishments in Egypt has grown to some
19,000 units, representing about 85 per cent of the total
industrial establishments.
</P>
<P>
The study shows that 19,191 of the total 22,493 industrial
ventures are small and medium-size establishments.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Al Aamar Real Estate company in the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) has embarked on its Al Marsa project which entails
the construction of an integrated residential town in the city of
Dubai at a total cost of 4.4 billion dollars, of which 350 million
dollars are allocated for the town's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The company is also planning to put up a tower in Dubai to be
named the "millennium," at a total cost of 57.19 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Investment Fund Lebanon Holdings said on Monday that
it has acquired a 30 percent stake in Liban Beton, a leading ready
mix concrete company.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star reported Tuesday that the purchase was
achieved through a cash-injection which has increased Liban
Beton's capital from 400,000 U.S. dollars to 3 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon has decided to delay the annual shopping
festival from January 20 to May, the Daily Star reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The postponement is intended to give businesses outside Beirut
to prepare for the month of discounts, Minister of Economy and
Trade Nasser Saidi was quoted as saying. 
</P>
