<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Olympic Council of Asia
(OCA) is in medal quandary after two more athletes tested
positive during the Asian Games, officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Two United Arab Emirates (UAE) athletes including Fakruddin
Taher, who won the silver in the 60-kilogramme kumite karate,
have been disqualified after failing drug tests.
</P>
<P>
Taher and unplaced 400-meter hurdler Abdulla Sabt tested
positive for the banned stimulant ephedrine on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
OCA Secretary General Randhir Singh told AFP that Taher had
been stripped of his medal, but it was unclear who would be the
new silver medallist as the karate event awarded two bronzes to
the losers of the semi-finals instead of holding a third-place
playoff.
</P>
<P>
"We have to decide on how to allocate the medal. The sports
committee of the OCA will be handling it," Randhir Singh was
quoted as saying. "We are going to have to give joint medals,
because they can't give a single one now."
</P>
<P>
He said the two bronze medallists would likely receive the
silver, while the bronzes would go to the next runners up.
</P>
