<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Capital to Get More Water Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Two projects that are
expected to increase water supply in the Ethiopian capital are
nearing completion, according to an announcement made by the
city's water and sewage service.
</P>
<P>
The current supply of water in the capital city, Addis Ababa,
is 60 percent of total demand. The projects will be able to
increase the water-supplying capacity to 85 percent of the
demand.
</P>
<P>
A press report said here Tuesday that Addis Ababa's water
shortage will be alleviated when the two projects begin to supply
114,000 cubic meters of water every day.
</P>
<P>
The two water supply projects, Dire emergency dam and Akaki
underground water development project, will be operational this
year.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-five percent of the work on Dire emergency dam project
is completed and it will soon go operational. The 30 million US
dollars project will supply the city with 42,000 cubic meters
every day.
</P>
<P>
The Akaki underground water development project which has a
total of 25 wells is expected to supply 72,000 cubic meters per
day once completed, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
