<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippines Response to Crisis Keeps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
indicated Tuesday that it has worked out its way to keep the
economy resilient amid the Asian economic crisis and to prepare it
for further consolidation and recovery next year.
</P>
<P>
"Our policy response worked well as 1998 proved the resilience
of the Philippine economy," the government said in its Year-End
Report on the Economy.
</P>
<P>
Emerging as one of the first positive-sign-showing Asian
countries, the Philippines has taken pains to cushion the economic
contagion's effects, including currency depreciation, financial
turmoil and economic slowdown or recession and tried to turn
around these things.
</P>
<P>
After more than one year, the measures taken to alleviate these
effects turned out to be the major contributors to the economic
resilience, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
On January 7, 1998, the Philippine currency peso reached its
trough of 45.40 pesos against the U.S. dollar, representing a
depreciation of about 41.9 percent from the pre-crisis level of
26.4 pesos.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, the Philippine Central Bank offered
the currency risk protection program to provide corporate
borrowers an instrument to hedge their foreign currency
obligations to foreign currency deposit units.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the peso has gradually stabilized and hit its
strongest performance of 38-39 pesos against the dollar in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
This protection program, combined with other regional and
domestic factors, resulted in the appreciation of the peso, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The next step was taken on the country's financial system.
</P>
<P>
One of the major differences between the Philippines and other
Asian countries is that the country has not had a financial crisis
and its financial system has remained inherently strong.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, reforms were continued to improve the transparency in
the banking system after the Asian crisis began, government
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Although the ratio of non-performing loans of the country's
banks to the total loan portfolio rose to 11.05 percent in August
this year, from 5.41 percent at the end of 1997, it was still
manageable.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, the International Monetary Fund projected that
the ratio for Thailand, Indonesia and South Koran could rise to
25-40 percent, 30-40 percent, and 25-30 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to spur the economy, the Philippines has opted to
expand its deficit and expenditure to boost investment and
domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 fiscal target was revised down from a surplus of 125
million U.S. dollars to a deficit of 1.2 billion dollars for the
whole 1998, the year-end report said. As of November, the deficit
stood at 1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the Philippine government has remained committed
to market-oriented policies and rejected the proposal to impose a
10-percent across-the-board tariff as well as a 50-percent
marginal deposit on letters of credit.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the gross national product (GNP) of the
Philippines is estimated to grow by about 0.5 percent to 1.0
percent this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
For 1999, the GNP is targeted to grow by 3.0 percent to 3.5
percent while gross domestic product is projected to grow by 2.6
percent to 3.1 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, as the measures are working to stabilize and
pump-prime the economy, the country has to weigh the balance
between these measures' short-run effects and the economy's
long-run objectives, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
That implies while all these measures keep the country from
slipping into a recession, they should not undermine the country's
long-run competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
After the test of the economy's resilience, this poses another
challenge to the country on its way to recovery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
