<HEADLINE> Investment Interest in Malaysia's Automotive Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian International
Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz said Tuesday that despite
the economic turmoil, investment interest has remained high in the
country's automotive industry.
</P>
<P>
Between January and October this year, her ministry approved 34
projects worth 655.8 million ringgit (about 172.578 million U.S.
dollars) in the field against 35 projects approved in 1997 worth
158.6 million ringgit (about 41.736 million dollars), Rafidah said
at a signing ceremony between Malaysia's Auto Trade (M) Sdn Bhd
and Indian-based vehicle manufacturer, Mahindra &AMP; Mahindra Ltd
here.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said that of the total 34 projects approved this year,
18 were new ones worth 595.4 million ringgit (about 156.684
million dollars) and 16 projects for expansion and diversification
worth 60.4 million ringgit (about 15.894 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The automotive industry has opened up opportunity for the
establishment and development of supportive sector, she said,
adding that so far there are 6,000 items already produced in
Malaysia, and it involved parts, components and accessories which
are related with the automotive trade.
</P>
<P>
She said the enhancement of the production parts and components
reflected the increased usage of local contents in the assembly
and manufacture of motor vehicles in which gross local content
currently stood at between 45 percent and 80 percent while net
local content is between 40 percent and 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
She said export performance of the automotive industry for both
motor vehicles and parts and accessories had been on the upward
trend with exports in 1996 totaling 948.5 million ringgit (about
249.605 million dollars), in 1997, totaling 1.075 billion ringgit
(about 282.894 million dollars) and 1.3316 billion ringgit (about
350.421 million dollars) between January and October this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
