<HEADLINE> East Asia Informal Summit A Success: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The recent second informal
summit between ASEAN and China, Japan and the Republic of Korea
(ROK) was a success and will exert a positive influence for
stability and development in Asia.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, leaders from several countries expanded
their common understanding and consolidated their confidence and
resolution for overcoming the financial crisis, said Zhu Bangzao,
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman, here today when asked to
comment on the summit, which took place in Hanoi, capital of
Vietnam, on December 16.
</P>
<P>
Chinese vice president Hu Jintao attended the meeting and
expressed China's views on the current world situation and
prospects for East Asia, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Hu stressed that although the financial crisis
brought difficulty to the region, the future of East Asia is still
bright due to its sound economic foundation.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that cooperation in East Asia must be in the
interest of all countries in the region, especially the developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
While the developed countries within and without the region
cooperate with developing nations by providing funds, the former
should also further open their commodity and technology markets to
the latter in order to enhance competitiveness and the capacity to
avoid crisis, Hu noted.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice president also said it is imperative to
strengthen inspection of the floating of short-term capital, and
establish dialogue within the mechanism of the East Asia informal
summit between vice ministers of finance and vice presidents of
central banks of the region's countries.
</P>
<P>
Hu also suggested setting up expert groups to study methods of
controlling floating capital.
</P>
<P>
Hu's proposals were welcomed and received positive responses at
the summit, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu added that during the meetings between Hu and leaders of
the ASEAN countries, the two sides reviewed progress in bilateral
relations since their first bilateral summit meeting in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that they will properly handle their
differences through comprehensive and cooperative mechanisms, and
adhere to the principle of equal and friendly consultation to push
forward the development of good-neighborly partnerships, Zhu
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
