<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tries Criminals in Accordance with Law: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese judicial departments
have full independence to try criminals, and all talk to the
contrary is unacceptable, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu
Bangzao said here today at his regular press conference.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remarks in response to questions about the recent
trials of three criminals who were sentenced for subversion of
state power in Chinese courts.
</P>
<P>
Xu Wenli, Wang Youcai and Qin Yongmin were found guilty of
subverting state power and were sentenced to 13, 12, and 11 years
in prison respectively, today and yesterday.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, it was confirmed in the Chinese courts that
Xu and other criminals contacted hostile overseas organizations
and accepted overseas financial assistance to engage in activities
to subvert state power and jeopardize state security.
</P>
<P>
Zhu indicated that their activities were in violation of
relevant provisions of the Criminal Law of the People's Republic
of China.
</P>
<P>
China's public security and judicial departments arrested and
tried Xu and others in accordance with Chinese law, "a normal case
in a country with the rule of law," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that the trial and punishment of criminals in
accordance with law are themselves judicial activities, and
"purely an internal matter of a sovereign state."
</P>
<P>
Zhu mentioned that China has noticed "some comments" from some
Western countries on the issue, saying that they are
"irresponsible and unreasonable." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's GDP Growth Increases by 6 Pct This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has realized its
National Assembly's adjusted target of a 6-percent GDP growth
despite flooding, drought and the regional economic crisis, The
Saigon Times Daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's industrial growth has been maintained at 12 percent
with state enterprises achieving a growth of 8.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The volume of major industrial products has increased
considerably, including crude oil (22.9 percent), cement (79.4
percent), steel (16 percent), motorcycle assembly (14 percent),
soap (28.6 percent), cardboard (21.7 percent) and beer (16.3
percent).
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's power generation has grown 13.9 percent, electric fan
production 68.8 percent, bicycles 40.5 percent, molasses, 18.8
percent, silk 12.4 percent and beer 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
Despite the drought and floods, Vietnam's agricultural
production has grown. The output of food (converted to paddy) has
reached 31.8 million tons, up more than one million tons from
1997. The agriculture, forestry and fishery sectors have achieved
an average growth of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The trading and service sectors have reported stable growth.
Total retail sales in 1998 are posted at 180,500 billion
Vietnamese Dong (about 13 billion U.S. dollars), a 14.2 percent
rise from last year.
</P>
<P>
However, "the Saigon times daily" said, the economic downturn,
low efficiency of business and production, falling demand, slow
economic restructuring, weaknesses in the banking and financial
system, and lavish spending have taken their toll.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the gap between rich and poor has widened and many
people in remote and flood-prone areas still lead difficult lives.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
