<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 09:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West Asian Countries' Economic Growth Down in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The average economic growth
rates for 13 Western Asian countries in 1998 will drop to 0.85
percent compared with 3 percent in 1997, a United Nations report
said.
</P>
<P>
The report was released on Monday by the Beirut-based
U.N. Economic and Social Commission for Western Asia (ESCWA), the
Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the low growth rates in the region mainly
to the sharp decline in oil prices and revenues in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices slumped 33.4 percent between 1997 and 1998, falling
from 18.68 U.S. dollars to 12.44 dollars a barrel on average,
while oil demand declined by 400,000 to 500,000 barrels per day in
the past year.
</P>
<P>
Thus, oil revenues in the region are down from 95 billion
dollars in 1997 to 68 billion dollars in 1998, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report also pointed to other factors likely to affect the
economic growth in the region, such as uncertainties over the
Middle East peace process and developments in the U.N. sanctions
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The report forecast an improvement in economic growth rate
estimated at 2.94 percent in 1999, taking into consideration
changes in oil prices in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
ESCWA groups Bahrain, Egypt, Iraq, Jordan, Kuwait, Lebanon,
Oman, Palestine, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Syria, the United Arab
Emirates and Yemen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economy Plunges Into Recession in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's economy, described
as one of the "tiger economies" before 1997, has plunged into
serious recession in 1998 following a prolonged monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
After hitting by the worst monetary crisis since July last
year, the value of the Indonesian rupiah has lost 60 percent
against the U.S. dollar. This year, government officials said,
Indonesia's gross domestic product (GDP) is expected to contract
around 14 percent compared with a positive growth of 6 percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the inflation rate has also increased to 80 percent
in 1998, about ten times higher than that of last year. As a
result, the people's living standard in the country has decreased
sharply with per capital GDP now stands at around 400 U.S.
dollars, down from a pre-crisis level of over 1,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Because of the close-down of many enterprises and banks, the
country's unemployment has risen substantially. Current estimates
put the number at 13 million. Underemployment is estimated at some
37 percent of about 90 million people in the labor force. More
than 70 million people out of a population of 202 million have
fallen below the poverty line. Some 30 million of them will
experience absolute poverty by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The deepening of the economic crisis has also led to a grave
political crisis which forced Soeharto who had ruled the country
for 32 years to step down from presidency.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to arrest the country's economic crisis, the
Indonesian government under the leadership of President B.J.
Habibie has taken some important measures, such as stabilizing the
exchange rate of rupiah, shifting the development priority from
heavy industry to small and medium-sized enterprises as well as
cooperatives which could absorb a huge labor force.
</P>
<P>
In a move to speed up the national economic recovery program,
Bank Indonesia has decided to extend liquidity credits totaling
10.8 trillion (1.46 billion U.S. dollars) to small-scale
businesses and cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
To revitalize the ailing banking sector, the Indonesian
government has begun recapitalizing 70 out of 166 national
commercial banks at a cost of 257.5 trillion rupiah (34.3 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Realizing the relative strength of the agricultural sector in
the economic crisis, the government had also decided to give
priority to the development of the sector.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government has making efforts to seek
assistance from international monetary bodies including the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), the World Bank, the Asian
Development Bank as well as some countries.
</P>
<P>
Most of analysts predicted that Indonesia's economic growth in
1999 will still be negative between 6 percent to 8 percent. They
said the economic recovery will largely depend on the political
stability in the country where a general election will be held in
June next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Preserve Stone Buddha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- China will spend ten million
yuan to preserve the Leshan Buddha, one of the world's great
cultural relics in southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
A National Tourism Administration official said this is the
largest preservation project for the stone Buddha since it was
first created 1,200 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The preservation work will include washing the Buddha's face,
establishing a water drainage system in its body, widening the
platform under the feet of the statue, and opening new routes to
divert tourists.
</P>
<P>
After decades of research, experts have found ways to preserve
the statue without causing any damage.
</P>
<P>
The central government, the Sichuan provincial government, and
the Leshan city all will collect funds, some of which will come
from a World Bank loan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
