<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT 0830, December 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE -- Namibia and Zimbabwe have denied reports from Angola
by UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi that they have troops in that
country to help President Jose Dos Santos's government fight the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
UNITA, the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola,
said in a statement earlier that Namibian and Zimbabwean troops
entered the country last Friday under the auspices of the Southern
African Development Community's security
organ. (Zimbabwe-Denial-Troops)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DHAKA -- The repatriation of Myanmar refugees staying in
Bangladesh has been stalled again less than one month after it
was resumed late November.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar authorities recently conveyed to Bangladesh that it
could not take back the Rohingya refugees during the Ramadan, the
holy month of fasting for Muslims across the
world. (Bangladesh-Myanmar-Refugees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Insulza said
here Monday that Chile might lodge an appeal with the Spanish
Supreme Court against the extradition of former president Augusto
Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
Insulza said that the Chilean government was waiting for a
response from Madrid to a letter it had sent to the Spanish
government requesting a report on what possible legal action would
be taken against Pinochet. (Chile-Pinochet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie Monday ordered an
immediate trial of 11 members of the Army's Special Forces
(Kopassus) allegedly involved the abductions of at least 24
pro-democracy activists some time ago.
</P>
<P>
"The president appreciated the Joint Fact-Finding Team findings
and their report," State Secretary/Minister Akbar Tanjung
said. (Indonesia-Probe-Abduction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The Indonesian government Monday admitted that
rapes had indeed occurred during the May rioting, but insisted
that their number was not high as had been previously reported.
</P>
<P>
Minister/State Secretary Akbar Tanjung said 52 women were
raped, 24 others were sexually assaulted, while four more victims
were sexually harassed. (Indonesia-Rape Cases)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan could be
extradited to Turkey for charges to which death penalty cannot be
applied, said an Italian prosecutor Monday.
</P>
<P>
Italian public prosecutor Giovanni Malerba told the Rome
Appeals Court that conditions existed to extradite the Kurdish
Worker's Party's (PKK) leader for trial on three of the charges
made in Turkey, but not for the other three because of the
possible death penalty. (Italy-Ocalan-Extradition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Monday voted 15-0
to adopt a resolution, calling for the establishment of a national
unity government in Guinea-Bissau and for holding elections in the
West African country by the end of March next year.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also urged the government and armed rebels to
carry out agreements they had reached, including a ceasefire and
an immediate opening of the airport and seaport in the nation's
capital of Bissau. (UN-Guinea-Bissau) 
</P>
</TEXT>
