<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman on China's Role in Iraqi Nuclear-Inspection Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- China has made active efforts
to urge the United States and Britain to stop military attacks
against Iraq as soon as possible and to avoid further
deterioration of the situation.
</P>
<P>
China's Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao made these
remarks here today in response to a question on China's role in
the Iraqi nuclear-inspection crisis.
</P>
<P>
Chinese president Jiang Zemin delivered an oral message
specially to U.S. president Bill Clinton and exchanged views over
the telephone with Russian president Boris Yeltsin, elaborating on
China's stance against the use of force, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese foreign minister Tang Jiaxuan sent an oral
message to his Russian counterpart, Igor Ivanov, pointing out that
the U.S. and Britain's unilateral use of force against Iraq
without authorization from the United Nations Security Council has
infringed upon the UN Charter and the norms of international law,
and stressing that seeking a political approach for resolving the
issue remains the top priority for the moment, according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China is maintaining close contact with parties
concerned at the UN Security Council and the capitals of several
countries, Zhu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
