<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo on Worries About Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo
Tuesday with the key Nikkei index closing below 14,000 for the first
time since November 2, reflecting investors' concern over Japan's
ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 373.50 points, or 2.64
percent, from Monday's close to end at 13,779.45.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 16.66 points or 1.52 percent to
1,082.46.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 354.65
million shares from Monday's 246.42 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Electric was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Investors cannot maintain a positive outlook for the Japanese
economy after Monday's report of the International Monetary Fund
(IMF), which said Japan's real gross domestic product for 1999 will
shrink 0.5 percent, a downward revision from a 0.5 percent rise
predicted in September, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Stocks moved lower in most business sectors, except for
pharmaceutical firms and nonbank money lenders, with 33 shares
falling to new lows for the year.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 827 to 315, with 150 issues ending unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
