<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Pudong New Area: New Treasure Trove </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Eight years ago, when Zhu
Rongji was mayor, the Pudong New Area was just a place for shabby
dwellings, narrow dirt paths, and patches of farmland.
</P>
<P>
But, the past eight years have turned it into a treasure trove
for Shanghai and it now generates more than 70 billion yuan (8.45
billion US dollars) in GDP, in sharp contrast to the 6 billion
yuan (725 million US dollars) in 1990.
</P>
<P>
By the end of November, it had approved 5,430 overseas-financed
enterprises, with contracts of 10.46 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Lujiazui Finance and Trade Zone on the Pujiang River's east
bank, is an example of the development. The 1.7-sq.km. zone was
built with a carefully-drafted plan.
</P>
<P>
A miniature of the design and a memento of the Pudong New Area
development office were recently added to the Museum of the
Chinese Revolution collection in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Lujiazui now has 180 high-rise buildings, including the
88-storey Jinmao Mansion, China's tallest. Its businesses are in
banking, securities, insurance, trusts, and investments and fill
24 of the high-rises. The Shanghai Securities Building, the
biggest transaction hall in Asia, is also in the zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
