<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 08:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahrain Calls for Review of Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Bahrain called for a
complete review of the U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq at its weekly
cabinet session this week, the UAE's Gulf News daily reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet meeting chaired by Crown Prince and Acting Prime
Minister Sheikh Hamad Bin Isa Al-Khalifa, "calls for a complete
review of sanctions, to ease the difficulties that these
sanctions have caused to the Iraqi people," the daily said.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet welcomed the halting of military strikes against
Iraq by the U.S. and Britain, stressing the need to seize the
opportunity to contain the crisis by seeking a diplomatic
solution.
</P>
<P>
"The need of the hour is a permanent solution within the
framework of international laws, and not the military option with
all its negative effects," said Mohammed Al-Muttawa, the Cabinet
Affairs and Information Minister.
</P>
<P>
"Such a solution should guarantee the application of the
Security Council resolutions and also offer an entire review of
the sanctions imposed on Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Bahrain also urged Iraq to cooperate with the
U.N. Security Council in implementing all the relevant
U.N. resolutions to alleviate and avoid further sufferings of the
Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq in 1990 for its invasion of
Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
