<HEADLINE> Zambia Drops Treason Charges Against Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has dropped its treason
charges against Zambia Democratic Congress (ZDC) President Dean
Mung'omba and Nakatindi Wina, a former senior official of the
ruling Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD), government-owned
Zambia Daily Mail reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lusaka High Court judge Japhet Banda Monday discharged them on
nolle prosequi six days after the duo were granted constitutional
bail by the same court.
</P>
<P>
In response to the state's entering of the nolle prosequi,
Banda said the state from the outset had no evidence against the
duo and had wrongfully set the criminal machinery against them,
indicating the state were acting under ulterior motives which
amounted to abuse of court process.
</P>
<P>
Mung'omba and Nakatindi Wina, expelled chairperson in charge
of women affairs of the MMD, were charged with treason together
with 77 army soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the state accused them of collaborating
with the soldiers in a foiled military coup in October, 1997 in
attempt to topple the elected government of President Frederick
Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
But during a course of six months' treason trial, none of the
over 100 witnessed called by the state have testified against the
two persons who have been detained by police for at least one
year.
</P>
<P>
After the court ruling, both Mung'omba and Nakatindi Wina,
asked the court to award them costs in the matter after being in
custody for a long time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
