<HEADLINE> Second Stray Missile Found in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- A second stray missile from the
U.S.-British strikes against Iraq was found in southern Iran,
local daily Tehran Times reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two-meter-long cruise missile was found on the highway
between Khorramshahr to Ahvaz in Khuzstan province which borders
Iraq, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
Another missile landed in a residential area in downtown
Khorramshahr Thursday morning at the start of the U.S.-British
attack on Iraq, causing no injuries but some damages.
</P>
<P>
Iran has lodged a strong protest to both London and Washington
on Thursday by summoning British charge d'affaires in Tehran
Nic Browne and the Swiss ambassador, whose embassy looks after
the United States interest in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iran considered the stray missile attack a "violation of
Iranian territorial integrity" and warned the U.S. and Britain
not to repeat such a mistake.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Washington expressed regret to Tehran over the stray
missile fell in Khorramshahr through the Swiss embassy in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Washington explained that it had no intention to violate the
territorial integrity of Iran and would probe into the errant fall
of its missile in Khorramshahr. 
</P>
</TEXT>
