<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Population Reaches 18.75 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- A big rise in the number of
migrants jumping visa categories helped drive Australia's
estimated population to around 18.75 million people in June,
official figures showed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The official Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said, the
number of people living in Australia at the end of the fiscal year
1997-98 (June 30, 1998), was 18,751,000.
</P>
<P>
The national population growth rate rose slightly during the
year to reach 1.22 percent, up from 1.17 percent in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
The ABS said net overseas migration - the difference between
arrivals and departures - increased from 87,000 to 106,200 people
in the year to June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The main reason for this was a big increase in those jumping
from a short-term visa category to a long-term or permanent
category - up from minus 7,300 in 1996-97 to 27,100 in 1997-98,
the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
The number of people leaving Australia permanently rose 12
percent while permanent arrivals rose two percent.
</P>
<P>
A drop in the number of births and a rise in the number of
deaths saw the natural increase in Australia's population dip five
percent on the previous year to 120,600 people in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The nation's households got smaller last year, with the average
number of people per household dropping from 2.8 people to 2.7
people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
