<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Doubled-edged Blade  by Zhou Shuchun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The much trumpeted process of
economic globalization has been under serious challenges in the
passing year as capital and production move among nations in an
accelerated way in the era of globalization.
</P>
<P>
Accelerated Trans-Nationalization of Capital and Production
</P>
<P>
The year 1998 has seen a huge wave of business merges and an
increasing financial domination in the world economy.
</P>
<P>
They occurred in virtually all sectors, from industry to
financial markets, with a view to lowering cost and increasing
competitiveness against the backdrop of over-production.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months of the year, merger deals across the
world totaled 383 billion U.S. dollars, outshining the record
total of last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, direct foreign investment is expected to rise by
10 percent over last year, reaching between 430 and 440 billion
dollars, according to a United Nations report on global investment.
</P>
<P>
In fact, economic globalization has come to take the form of
direct investment in production and, in particular, the real
estate, financial services and information sectors, rather than
the traditional pattern of trade.
</P>
<P>
Despite a reduced growth rate of world economy, financial
capital across the globe has increased by 30 percent in the past
12 months. The ratio of transaction in foreign exchange as against
trade stands around 60:1 at the moment, compared with 10:1 in the
early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
By now, over 50,000 multi-nationals, together with hundreds of
thousands of branches and affiliates, have formed a colossal
network of production and sales covering all parts of the world.
They account for one-third of production, two-thirds of trade, 70
percent of total direct investment and over 70 percent of patent
rights and transfer of technology across the world.
</P>
<P>
A Double-Edged Blade
</P>
<P>
Despite its literal sense, economic globalization has meant
different stories for different countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the current economic order, the developed world continues
to take the lion's share of the globalization cake, and the
developing countries, supporting three-fourths of the world
population, are facing a "double-edged blade" of the process.
</P>
<P>
Globalization allows developing economies access to capital
flows and advanced technology, but giving the reins to foreign
conglomerates. In addition, the new pattern of global industrial
division poses serious environmental and ecological threats to
them, facilitated by an unchecked migration of pollution-causing
and resource-exhausting industries.
</P>
<P>
Based on the Breton Woods agreement half a century ago, the
international financial system has proved insufficient for an
entirely different environment created by economic globalization
and the laws of cross-border capital flow today. This has been
best manifested by the year-long Asian financial crisis which
spilled over to become a full-fledged international turmoil this
summer.
</P>
<P>
The world trade growth is expected to fall by 50 percent from
last year to between 4 and 5 percent this year. With an apparent
rise of protectionism, free trade -- an essential facet of
globalization -- is running up against more barriers.
</P>
<P>
Globalization Calls for New Economic Order
</P>
<P>
As Director-General of the World Trade Organization Renato
Ruggiero put it, the financial chaos this year marks "an important
turning point" in the process of globalization, and the world has
yet to learn how to adapt to an increasingly complicated global
economic system of inter-dependence.
</P>
<P>
General consensus has been reached that supervision and
regulation are necessary for the global markets, while the
emerging markets should be allowed to open up in a cautious and
measured manner.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the north and the south has become more than
ever a hazard, or "time bomb" as in the words of World Bank
President James Wolfensohn, for the security of world economy.
This calls for more official assistance and technology transfer to
the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, the traditional pattern of a small group of
industrialized nations sketching the global map of economic
development runs counter to the tides of globalization. There have
been increasing calls for the participation of more players,
including the developing countries and economies in transition, in
the top decision-making process of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
This past eventful year serves to show that only with the
establishment of a reasonable and just international economic
order, whereby all countries benefit to the maximum possible
extent, can economic globalization proceed on a smooth track and
fulfill its promise to ensure long-term stability and prosperity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
