<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's per capita annual
income has grown from 95 U.S. Dollars in 1995 to 143 Dollars in
1998.
</P>
<P>
This was announced in an investigation report the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP) issued here Monday, the
Noticias daily published here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report, the first human development report done by UNDP,
is aimed to offer the latest reliable statistics on Mozambicans
living condition, Emmenanuel de Casterle, the UNDP representative
to Mozambique, said at the launching ceremony of the report.
</P>
<P>
The report divides Mozambicans into three categories, namely,
the poor, the middle class and the rich, whose annual incomes are
respectively 50 Dollars, 100 Dollars and 150 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
It will take 14.2 years for the poor to reach the 150 U.S.
Dollar class, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report printed in both English and Portuguese, said that
Mozambique's GDP in 1998 is predicted at 2.2 billion Dollars.
