<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
took its lead from Wall Street Tuesday to close firmer, with
Christmas window dressing by fund managers the driving force
behind the surge in key industrial stocks, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index stacked on 21.8 points to
close at 2,759.8, coming off an intra-day high of 2,772.3.
</P>
<P>
"We're obviously strong on the back of what happened on Wall
Street overnight," Macquarie Nevitts client adviser Steve Mayne
said.
</P>
<P>
On Australian equities markets, the all resources index added
1.7 points to 962.5, while the all industrials index climbed 44.8
points to 4,957.4.
</P>
<P>
Mayne said resources stocks had a mostly subdued day on the
back of weaker commodity prices overnight.
</P>
<P>
"There was a bit of Christmas window dressing from fund
managers," he said, who were trying to make their books look
better for the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The bank index added 18.3 points to 6,327.5, with ANZ bank the
only major player to lose ground, shedding seven cents to 10.68
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank rose 11 cents to 24.71 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia rallied 9.1 cents to
22.291 Australian dollars and Westpac bank firmed two cents to
10.47 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resource sector, global miner Rio Tinto defied the
downward trend among the diversified stocks, surging 59.4 cents to
19.42 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Australia's leading company BHP off-loaded 6.9 cents to 12.031
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index eased 2.9 points to 1,094.1.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney on Tuesday afternoon
was 289.65 U.S. dollars an ounce, compared to a close of 289.90
U.S. dollars Monday.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary national turnover was 387.52 million stocks
changing hands for 670 million U.S. dollars, with rising stocks
outnumbering falling stocks 587 to 460 and 405 stocks remaining
steady. 
</P>
