<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Superannuation Assets Total 225b U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Australia's superannuation
assets rose to 364.6 billion Australian dollars (225 billion U.S.
dollars) at the end of September, 1998, the official Australian
Prudential Regulation Authority (APRA) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In its latest bulletin released, APRA, a newly-established
government body, said total assets were up nine percent on the
previous year, with equity and trust holdings accounting for 36.8
percent of the total assets, down slightly.
</P>
<P>
Interest-bearing securities accounted for 24.9 percent, up
slightly.
</P>
<P>
Self-managed funds, including small funds with five or fewer
members, experienced the strongest growth, with assets in this
part of the market growing by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The July 1998 increase in the compulsory employer contribution
rate from six to seven percent contributed to a 15-percent
increase in assets to 13.51 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The number of member superannuation accounts rose three percent
during the September quarter to 18.8 million.
</P>
<P>
Contributions during the year to September 1998 totaled 22
billion U.S. dollars, up from 18.35 billion U.S. dollars in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Benefit payments rose 13.1 percent in the year to September,
totaling 13.2 billion U.S. dollars, up from 11.6 billion U.S.
dollars in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Assets directly invested by trustees showed the strongest
growth during the September quarter, up 2.1 percent, while
investment managers had 39.1 percent of the total superannuation
assets, or 88.35 billion U.S. dollars, at the end of the quarter,
up from 38.8 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The share of superannuation assets invested overseas fell
during the September quarter to 15.7 percent, or 35.5 billion U.S.
dollars, down 1.79 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Prudential Regulation Authority said the change
in mix of investments suggested more volatile equity and overseas
markets had led to superannuation funds adopting a more defensive
investment strategy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
