<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Current Account Deficit Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- There has been a small
improvement in the deficit in New Zealand's current account, which
 measures the difference between how much it spends and buys.
</P>
<P>
Statistics New Zealand said Tuesday that in the year to
September, New Zealand spent 6.5 billion N.Z. dollars (3.38
billion U.S. dollars) more than it earned overseas.
</P>
<P>
That compares with a deficit of 6.2 billion N.Z. dollars (3.22
billion U.S. dollars) in the year to June, and a fractionally
higher deficit in the year to September 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, Statistics NZ said that on a seasonally adjusted
basis, the current account deficit improved between the second
and third quarters of this year.
</P>
<P>
Exports of commodities were up by 597 million N.Z. dollars (310
 million U.S. dollars) in the third quarter, it said.
</P>
<P>
This was an improved export performance despite the Asian
economic downturn, though the second quarter result had been
particularly bad, N.Z. Deputy Government Statistician Ian Ewing
said in the media release. 
</P>
