<HEADLINE> Hunan Province Reinforcing Flood Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Water conservation projects
have helped flood control in central-south China's Hunan Province,
while generating 38 billion yuan (4.6 billion US dollars) in
direct profits, according to a report in a recent issue of "China
Water Resources News."
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper quoted an official from the
provincial government as saying that Hunan has more than two
million water conservation projects, including 250 large and
medium-sized reservoirs, 5,800 kilometers of dikes, and 94
embarkments.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that in 1997, the provincial government spent
three billion yuan (362 million US dollars) for flood
control. Hunan has also set up over 300 hydrologic stations.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the first-phase flood control project for Tongting
Lake, after eleven years of construction, stood firm during this
past summer's floods.
</P>
<P>
Because of its efficient flood-control efforts, Hunan Province
succeeded in combating floods this summer by holding back three
billion cubic meters of water, thereby saving 15 billion yuan.
(1.8 billion US dollars). 
</P>
