<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's largest Coal Supplier to Close Illegal Coal Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province
has mapped out a plan to shut down 2,908 illegal coal mines by the
end of next year, 11 percent of all the coal mines under the state
plans to close.
</P>
<P>
This move is aimed at cutting coal output by 69.8 million tons
annually, which will account for 30 percent of China's targeted
amount to be reduced.
</P>
<P>
In the first three quarters this year, China's key coal firms
reported large deficits resulting from oversupply of coal.
Economists attribute the glut to rampant production by
small coal mines, which produced 46.6 percent of the country's
coal last year.
</P>
<P>
Shutting down coal mines that are operating illegally or have
been planned irrationally is a major step in the current reform to
pull the coal industry out of stagnation.
</P>
<P>
The central government has decided to close some 25,800 small
coal mines to bring annual national output down by some 250
million tons by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
Coal mining is a major industry in Shanxi where one-quarter of
the country's coal output is produced annually. The province has
eight key state-owned coal mines employing a total of one-million
people.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities have drafted specific measures to implement
the closings, and the province will not approve any more coal
mines during the closure period. Certificates will no longer be
granted to these small coal mines, nor will they any longer have
access to transportation, sales or operational facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Official on Economic Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
Tuesday described 1998 as a year of proving its economic
resilience and was optimistic about the prospects for further
consolidation and recovery in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Felipe Medalla, the Philippines' Socioeconomic Planning
Secretary and Director-General of National Economic and
Development Authority, told reporters that the country's economy
has avoided a recession and is now assured of a positive growth of
Gross National Product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Releasing the 1998 Year-End Report on the Economy, Medalla said
the government estimates the GNP would grow by about 0.5 to 1.0
percent this year with a 0.8 percent of growth for the first three
quarters.
</P>
<P>
Medalla said the crucial recovery of agriculture and industry
would likely drive the GNP up to 3.0 to 3.5 percent and Gross
Domestic Product (GDP) to 2.6 to 3.1 percent for 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said that in responding to economic challenge, the
government has taken measures of overcoming short-run problems,
achieving long-run goals, and balancing economic, fiscal and
social objectives.
</P>
<P>
He cited these measures as stabilizing and pump priming the
economy, strengthening the financial system, carrying out
market-oriented policies and protecting the vulnerable sectors.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, with the economy slowed down, the average
unemployment rate registered in the first three Labor Force
Surveys this year rose to 10.3 percent from 9 percent a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
With the depreciation of the Philippine currency peso and the
effect of El Nino on food prices, inflation accelerated, he said.
The average inflation rate for January to November stood at an
average of 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the exchange rate adjustments also brought about the
reversal of country's trade position from a deficit of 9.5 billion
U.S. dollars a year ago to a much smaller deficit of 838 million
dollars in the first 10 months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Medalla anticipated that the probability of a recovery in 1999
will be stronger as the government generates additional foreign
financing for its programmed deficit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the proposed budget for 1999, if finally approved by
Congress, remains pro-growth and pro-poor, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
