<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Coffee Production Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's coffee output rose to
12,865 tons in the first quarter of fiscal 1998/99 year compared
with just 4,812 tons in the same period of 1997/98, according to
the Coffee Board of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The board spokesman Paul Kivila said Monday that crop intake
in the first quarter (which runs from October to December) was a
vast improvement over the miserable showing a year ago, he was
quoted by The People newspaper Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Coffee crop in Kenya fell to just 47,000 tons in 1997/98 and
traders here have forecast a crop of 52,000 tons in 1998/99.
</P>
<P>
Kivila said it was to early to forecast 1998/99 production,
adding that poor weather was still a problem.
</P>
<P>
"We have done well in terms of production in the first
quarter. Prices have also been firm and real farm earning have
been good," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there is still cause of concern. "Rains are not
sufficient in crop growing areas and this is causing some worry
about the year's total crop figure." 
</P>
</TEXT>
