<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Man Gets Prison Sentence for Subverting State Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- An intermediate people's court
in Wuhan, the capital of China's Hubei Province, found Qin Yongmin
guilty of subverting state power and sentenced him to 12 years in
prison today.
</P>
<P>
Qin was also deprived of political rights fro three years by the
Wuhan Intermediate People's Court.
</P>
<P>
In an open trial, the court found that, in November this year,
Qin secretly planned to found the "Hubei Provincial Committee of
the China Democratic Party", an illegal organization, with the
purpose of subverting state power and the socialist system.
</P>
<P>
The court also found that Qin had formulated "constitution" and
"announcement" about the "party" and sought and accepted funds from
some hostile overseas organizations to organize, plan and conduct
subversive activities.
</P>
<P>
A court investigation found that Qin had used various means to
stir up subversive activities since March of this year. After
hearing arguments by prosecutors and the defense, the court ruled
that, in accordance with China's Criminal Law, Qin's activities
constituted the crime of subverting state power, that Qin is a
recidivist, and that he should be punished accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Qin's family and members of the public were present at today's
court hearing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
