<HEADLINE> hke122225 -Australia-PNG Ministerial Forum Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australia-Papua New
Guinea (PNG) Ministerial Forum concluded its two-day meeting
Tuesday in Cairns, the northeast city of the country.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement released at the end of the meeting, the
PNG government's approach to the Bougainville peace process was
described as "constructive and flexible."
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said during a
post- forum news conference that in spite of the failure of the
PNG parliament to pass crucial legislation needed to set up the
Bougainville reconciliation government, he personally hoped the
PNG parliament would resume and pass the legislation.
</P>
<P>
"But I am satisfied the commitment is there to put together
workable arrangements," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
"There are interim arrangements in place to support the peace
process and there would be problems if we withdrew, but how long
it will go on depends on how the peace process moves forward," he
said.
</P>
<P>
PNG Foreign Minister Roy Yaki emphasized the need for the
continuation of the Bougainville aid program.
</P>
<P>
"The Peace Monitoring Group must not become a permanent
fixture," Yaki said.
</P>
<P>
"The aid program is a high priority, because it delivers a
peace dividend in the form of restoration and reconstruction."
</P>
<P>
Australia responded to the request by agreeing to speed up
spending on roads and a peace travel fund, and to continue with
assistance in training a Bougainville police force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
