<HEADLINE> Chinese Ducks Go On Hunger Strike When Separated From Drakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Some ducks at a farm in the
city of Jixi in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province refused to
drink or eat anything recently when they were separated from the
drakes, according to today's Beijing Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
The Zhenghe Duck Farm had some 10,000 ducks and used to keep
them together because workers couldn't tell the ducks from the
drakes when they were hatched.
</P>
<P>
But, when workers recently moved the drakes to other places for
greater efficiency, the ducks went on a hunger strike the very
same day.
</P>
<P>
And, they returned to their food and water when they were
reunited with the drakes, the paper reports.
</P>
<P>
One experienced duck keeper says that ducks and drakes do not
normally have the habit of living and playing together, and are
not known for their loyalty to each other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
