<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Namibia and Zimbabwe have
denied reports from Angola by UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi that
they have troops in that country to help President Jose Dos
Santos's government fight the rebels.
</P>
<P>
UNITA, the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola, said in a statement earlier that Namibian and Zimbabwean
troops entered the country last Friday under the auspices of the
Southern African Development Community's security organ.
</P>
<P>
The Herald newspaper in Zimbabwe reported Tuesday that
Brigadier Mathias Shiweda, chief of staff operations in the
Namibian Defense Force, said that his country did have troops
helping United Nations forces with demining operations, but it
had not sent any troops to back the Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
He said, "there is no such thing. UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi
should not try and derail the peace process by claiming that we
are threatening him by supporting the Angolan government forces."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a senior official, who was not named, of the
Zimbabwean Defense Ministry Monday said that Zimbabwe had not
sent troops into Angola, according to the daily Herald.
</P>
<P>
But on his way back from a meeting in Ouagadougou, Burkina
Faso, at the weekend, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said
Savimbi was a war criminal who must be sought and defeated. He
urged all countries to isolate him.
</P>
<P>
This may have been misconstrued to mean that Zimbabwe and
Namibia will hunt down Savimbi, said the Zimbabwean official.
</P>
