<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Looking for Ways To Save Endangered South China Tiger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- China has established a gene
bank for the South China Tiger and a training center to get them
to return to nature.
</P>
<P>
The gene bank has semen from 30 South China Tigers for future
artificial insemination of the endangered species. There are only
53 of the animals in Chinese zoos or nature reserves and only 9
females of child-bearing age.
</P>
<P>
It is China's only remaining tiger species. Its life span is
usually 20 years. Its number have dwindled to even fewer than the
endangered giant panda.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Wild Animal Breeding Center has a program to
rescue the South China Tiger and is focusing on ways to breed the
animal and study their movements.
</P>
<P>
In October, the State Forestry Administration established a
South China Tiger nature reserve in Fujian Province and moved 5 of
the tigers there from zoos in other provinces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
