<HEADLINE> U.S. Ex-IOC Member Blames Olympic Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A group of International
Olympic Committee members have used blocks of votes in seeking
for extravagant gifts and favors from the Olympics bidding
cities, a resigned IOC member from the United States said today.
</P>
<P>
Robert Helmick, who resigned from the IOC and as president of
the U.S. Olympic Committee in 1991, said the gifts could range
from fur coats to shopping sprees for members'wives.
</P>
<P>
He also said that $5,000 to $10,000 in first-class airfare for
each member and spouse was "the minimun that's expected before
they get to the gifts. That's tit for tat."
</P>
<P>
Helmick refused to identify any IOC members or bid committees
involved in corruption.
</P>
<P>
"It's the system. It's people without a constituency dealing
with a lot of money, without checks and balances. That leads to
corruption without the people being corrupt."
</P>
<P>
Helmick pointed out that "there are several IOC members who
control blocks of votes who are willing to deliver them for
extravagant gifts and favors."
</P>
<P>
Helmick said he never was approached by a bid city offering
enticements during his five years on the IOC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
