<HEADLINE> Ewing Calls League's Deal No Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Patrick Ewing, the New
York Knicks star and union president, has different idea from
Karl Malone about NBA's latest offer. He doesn't think the
proposal "fair" and "decent".
</P>
<P>
"The deal is the same deal we've been going over for the last
two or three weeks -- maybe even longer," Ewing said. "They
haven't changed their position. All they did was make the numbers
look great, but it's not a good deal."
</P>
<P>
Malone called the offer "fair and decent" yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The union's negotiating committee held an internal meeting
Monday with about 125 players listening in on a conference call.
</P>
<P>
It was the ninth day since the sides met, and players continue
to lose $50 million a week in salaries as the lockout drags on.
No new talks are scheduled. Commissioner David Stern is on
vacation.
</P>
<P>
If a deal isn't reached soon, the entire season will be
scrapped. Sonics center Jim McIlvaine supported Ewing.
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot of stumbling blocks in order to make the deal
and the big one is control," McIlvaine said. "Thay could be a
presidential definition of 'tweak'. 'Tweak' for him could mean a
major modification for someone else.
</P>
<P>
"If you look at the numbers, they look good. The superstars
are going to get their money, but we're trying to take care of
the guys in the middle." 
</P>
