<HEADLINE> Japanese Cabinet Approves Spy Satellites Launch Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese cabinet Tuesday
approved a plan to launch information-gathering satellites by the
2002 financial year in a bid to boost the country's reconnaissance
capability.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Japan will launch four satellites, said
Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka, who added that two
of them will be optical, while the other two will use radar,
allowing them to function even in bad weather.
</P>
<P>
In a draft budget for fiscal 1999 approved Monday by the
cabinet, the Science and Technology Agency, which will be in
charge of making and launching the satellites, was allocated 6.8
billion yen (about 58.6 million U.S. dollars) for the plan.
</P>
<P>
Japan announced the launching plan after the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea fired a rocket in August 31. Part of
the rocket, which Japan claimed was a multistage ballistic
missile, flew over Japan into the Pacific. 
</P>
</TEXT>
