<HEADLINE> Cambodian Govt Appointees Vacate Parliament Posts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of parliamentarians
vacated their seats in the National Assembly Tuesday after the
assembly approved a draft law barring government officials from
holding parliamentary positions.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, about 14 newly elected Cambodian People's Party
(CPP) parliamentarians and 16 FUNCINPEC lawmakers who have been
appointed ministers or secretaries of state as well as other state
high rankings have vacated their seats in the new parliament.
</P>
<P>
Among them are Chea Sim, CPP President and the would-be
president of the Senate, Khieu Kanarhidh, Secretary of State for
Information, Prince Sisowath Sirirath, co-Minister of Defense, and
Uk Vithun, Minister of Justice.
</P>
<P>
Their positions were filled by colleagues appointed by their
parties according to the party candidate list. New
parliamentarians were already sworn in Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The move could drastically alter the face of the assembly, as
ministers and state secretaries held more than 20 seats in the
last parliament. One pro-democracy activist hailed the move as a
boost to the independence of the legislative branch from the
executive.
</P>
<P>
Ky Lam Ang, a member of the assembly's Permanent Committee,
said that making sure parliamentarians hold only one job should
make it easier for the nine key commissions in the parliament to
achieve quorums.
</P>
<P>
Lack of quorums in commissions is now holding up the draft
budget law and draft constitutional amendments to create a Senate.
Over the past year, failures to meet quorums have delayed Assembly
efforts to pass election legislation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
