<HEADLINE> Thailand Still Prepared to Evacuate Nationals in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is still prepared to
evacuate its nationals from Iraq although U.S. and British
warplanes has stopped strikes against that country, foreign
ministry officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Thailand believed that tension remained high in the region
despite the end of the air strikes, said the officials.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain launched a series of air attacks
against Iraq last week, alleging that Iraq failed to destroy its
mass-destructive weapons in light with relevant U.N. resolutions.
The strikes ended on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The tension is still high in Iraq although the U.S. and the
U.K. have halted their assault on the country," Thai Foreign
Ministry spokesman Kobsak Chutikul said.
</P>
<P>
All Thais, mostly students who had volunteered to evacuate in
the wake of last week's air strikes, have returned to their
residences in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"The Thai Embassy in Baghdad will work with the Indonesian and
Filipino embassies to urge the Iraqi authorities to permit Thai
students to cross into Jordan if an evacuation gets underway. We
will also ask Iraq to allow the students to re-enter the country
after the crisis ends," Kobsak said. 
</P>
