<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Grants $2.5 Billion Loan to Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Interamerican
Development Bank (IDB) has agreed on its biggest ever loan in an
agreement on Monday with Argentina worth 2.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
IDB President Enrique Iglesias said the funds would be used to
"deepen second-generation reforms implemented by Argentina".
</P>
<P>
The loan has a seven-year term with a three-year grace
period. It has a rate equivalent to the London Interbank Offering
Rate (Libor) plus four percentage points, totalling nine percent.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, two billion dollars will be channeled to
Argentina's program of industrial sector reform while the
remaining 500 million will go to strengthen bank security networks.
</P>
<P>
Another loan of one billion dollars will be given immediately
to Argentina for foreign debt repayments due at the end of this
month, while the rest will be released in the first three months
of next year.
</P>
<P>
Iglesias said that in 1998 the IDB approved a total of 3.6
billion dollars in loans for Argentina, the biggest ever amount in
the bank's history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exports Fall by 3.3 Percent in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's total export volume
fell by 3.3 percent year-on-year in October, the first such drop
since the baht was floated in July last year, the Commerce
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Although Thailand continued to register a trade surplus for 14
consecutive months, October export values shrank by 12.7 percent
in dollar terms to 4.63 billion U.S. dollars, its eighth
consecutive month of fall, the ministry said in a report, made
public on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The drop occurred in all product categories especially
agriculture and the agro-industry which witnessed a fall in values
by 14.6 percent and 20.4 percent, respectively, while volumes
decreased by 9.5 percent and 36.3 percent, respectively," said the
report.
</P>
<P>
In baht terms, exports showed a 7.5 percent year-on-year
decline against a 36.9 percent rise during January-October 1998.
Thai exporters have criticized the government for allowing the
baht to get stronger compared with currencies of competing
countries.
</P>
<P>
During the 10-month period, Thailand's exports dipped by 6.4
percent to 45.28 billion dollars. Export volumes increased
continuously by an average of 9 percent, but export prices were
down by 14.3 percent, mainly on agriculture and agro-industry
products..
</P>
<P>
For manufactured exports, prices also faced downward pressure
due to increased competition from South Korea and China,
especially for ready-made garments, fabrics, footwear and plastic
parts and products.
</P>
<P>
On imports, shipments in dollar terms fell by 35.2 percent in
the first 10 months, compared with the same period last year.
Imports in October went down by 23.7 percent, the 16th consecutive
monthly fall.
</P>
<P>
In baht terms, imports fell by 3.4 percent year-on-year, with
October imports falling by 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
The October trade surplus was 1.01 billion dollars, the 13th
consecutive month of trade surplus. Surpluses are recorded with
the U.S., the EU, and ASEAN (excluding Malaysia), but Thailand
still has trade deficits with Japan, the Middle East, Malaysia,
Australia, China's Taiwan, China and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
A sharp decline in imports is due to low local demand, a
slowdown of investment and the intensified liquidity crunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
