<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt to Finalize Probe of Abduction Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Monday ordered an immediate trial of 11 members of the
Army's Special Forces (Kopassus) allegedly involved the abductions
of at least 24 pro-democracy activists some time ago.
</P>
<P>
"The president appreciated the Joint Fact-Finding Team findings
and their report," State Secretary/Minister Akbar Tanjung said.
</P>
<P>
"He (Habibie) has ordered an immediate trial of Kopassus
members in order to establish the possible involvement of former
Commander of Army Strategic Reserve Command (Kostrad) Lt. Gen.
(ret.) Prabowo Subianto in the abduction of activists," Akbar
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister, however, did not disclose the contents of the
Joint Fact-Finding Team findings, according to national newspapers
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo, a son-in-law of former president Soeharto, was chief
of Kopassus when the kidnappings took place. He has admitted his
wrong-doing in the abductions of more than 20 political activists
early this year and said he would be responsible for the cases.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo commanded Kopassus for more than two years before he
was appointed commander of Kostrad last March. Prabowo was
permanently discharged from military service after he admitted
that he had presided over a number of the abductions, and
officially became a retired lieutenant general on December 10.
</P>
<P>
Akbar said the government would soon finish its investigations
on members of Kopassus suspected of being involved in the
abductions of political activists.
</P>
<P>
"The process will be aimed at ascertaining the extent of
retired Lt. Gen. Prabowo's involvement in the cases," Akbar told
reporters after a meeting between Habibie and a number of cabinet
ministers who discussed the government's position regarding the
team's findings.
</P>
<P>
According to Coordinator of the Commission for Missing Persons
and Victims of Violence Munir, the trial of 11 members of Kopassus
will start Wednesday at a military court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
