<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Singapore Jointly Train Skilled Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- A workers' training and testing
center has been opened here to turn out more skilled Myanmar
workers to meet the standard of Construction Industry Development
Board (CIDB) of Singapore under the country's overseas employment
program.
</P>
<P>
The center, jointly established by the Myanmar Department of
Labor and the Sinmar Tech Co Ltd of Singapore, costs about 233,000
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the center Monday, Myanmar
Minister of Labor Major-General Tin Ngwe said Myanmar wants to
acquire advanced technique and skills with a view to the
furtherance of transfer of technology.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Singapore have conducted skill training courses for
carpentry and bar-bending and more than 400 skilled Myanmar
workers, who met the standard of CIDB of Singapore, have been sent
for employment there.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is also participating in a project for human resources
development to be implemented in the greater Mekong sub-region
initiated by the Asian Development Bank. One component of the
project is for employment promotion and skill development.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar proposed for the initial phase the skill standard on
six trades -- carpentry, plumbing and pipe-fitting, welding,
electrical and electronics, refrigeration and air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is formulating programs for training of qualified and
skilled workers in 10 selected trades to challenge the growing
demand for skilled workers in the emerging industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
