<HEADLINE> Chile Could Appeal in Spain's Supreme Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Chilean Foreign Minister Jose
Miguel Insulza said here Monday that Chile might lodge an appeal
with the Spanish Supreme Court against the extradition of former
president Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
Insulza said that the Chilean government was waiting for a
response from Madrid to a letter it had sent to the Spanish
government requesting a report on what possible legal action would
be taken against Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, whose 18-year dictatorship saw the deaths or
disappearances of thousands of political opponents, has been under
arrest in London for over two months, at the request of Spanish
Judge Baltazar Garzon who asked for his extradition to Spain for
trial.
</P>
<P>
Garzon said that Pinochet should be held responsible for the
deaths of many innocent people including some foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Insulza said that Chile's Senate President Andres Zaldivar, who
returned from a trip to Europe to lobby for Pinochet's return, had
told him that the Chilean government's stand was being viewed with
"respect and understanding". 
</P>
