<HEADLINE> Thai Muslims Collect Donations for Iraqis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Muslim organizations in
southern Thailand said they would send donations to fellow Muslims
in Iraq and boycott American products in protest against the
U.S.-led bombing attacks on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
About 50 representatives of the Islamic committees of the five
southernmost provinces, private Islamic groups and Muslim student
organizations agreed on the action during their meeting in the
southern province of Yala on Monday, Tuesday's Nation newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
Monday's resolution was in line with an earlier platform
adopted by the Association of Moslem Youths of Thailand against
the bombing of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Association president Anantachai Thaiprathan was quoted as
saying the group was soliciting donations for suffering fellow
Muslims in Baghdad and will submit a protest letter to the U.S.
and British embassies.
</P>
<P>
The association would launch a campaign to boycott imported and
locally-produced merchandise of U.S. and British brands by
circulating a letter to Muslim organizations nationwide to seek
their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
It would open a website next week for Thai Muslims to express
their opinions about the attacks on Iraq, said Anantachai.
</P>
<P>
The group would also demand the government clearly show its
official stand towards the attacks.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to go forward in the long term. We do not want the
move to be just a provisional reaction to the attacks," Anantachai
said.
</P>
<P>
Thai Muslims would also cooperate with international Muslim
organizations to protest against the attacks on Iraq and
scrutinize the United Nations for its failure to stop such use of
force, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British warplanes raided Baghdad in a series of
attacks last week for Iraq's alleged defiance of U.N. resolutions
on the destruction of the country's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
