<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Norway Has No Plan to Join EU, Says PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Norwegian Prime Minister
Kjell Magne Bondevik said Monday that Norway has no plan to join
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Christmas press conference in Oslo, Bondevik said
that Norway will increase its cooperation with the EU through the
European Free Trade Association (EFTA) and the European Economic
Area.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, it does not mean that Norway will join the EU.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Norway, Switzerland, Austria, Sweden, Demark and
Portugal are the seven formal members of the EFTA, which was set
up in 1960. The seven countries formed the European Economic Area
in 1992, setting the free flow of commodities, people, capital and
labor as its goal.
</P>
<P>
Bondevik dismissed the view that it is time to reconsider the
entry issue since great changes have taken place since 1994, when
a national referendum prevented Norway from joining the EU.
</P>
<P>
This kind of view is not correct, Bondevik said.
</P>
<P>
Since Norway is one of the most advanced countries in the
world, it lost nothing in staying outside the EU, he said. On the
contrary, Norway is getting very well under the current situation,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
