<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls for Unity Government in Guinea-Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Monday voted 15-0 to adopt a resolution, calling for the
establishment of a national unity government in Guinea-Bissau and
for holding elections in the West African country by the end of
March next year.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also urged the government and armed rebels to
carry out agreements they had reached, including a ceasefire and
an immediate opening of the airport and seaport in the nation's
capital of Bissau.
</P>
<P>
The resolution appealed for the withdrawal of foreign troops
from the former Portuguese colony and the simultaneous deployment
of a force of the West African peace-keepers, known as ECOMOG, in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The force is meant to keep the two sides apart and guarantee
security along the border with Senegal, which sent troops to
support President Joao Bernardo Vieira after fighting broke out on
June 7 between loyalist forces and fired army chief Ansumane Mane.
</P>
<P>
The council asked Secretary-General Kofi Annan to make
recommendations on a possible U.N. role in the process of peace
and reconciliation in Guinea-Bissau, including the early
establishment of an arrangement for liaison between the United
Nations and ECOMOG. 
</P>
</TEXT>
