<HEADLINE> Venezuela, Mexico Hold Talks on Further Oil Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President-elect
Hugo Chavez met with Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo on Monday
to discuss fresh cuts to crude oil production.
</P>
<P>
Chavez earlier had said his "urgent" talks with Zedillo would
include oil policy, after Venezuela, Mexico and Saudi Arabia met
last week in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
Mexican Energy Minister Luis Tellez, who met with Chavez a week
ago in Caracas, had said after the Madrid meeting new cuts could
be implemented to reverse a 25-year low in prices.
</P>
<P>
Chavez has stated his administration, scheduled to take office
in February, would respect current oil production cuts until the
end of next year.
</P>
<P>
Mexico had earlier criticized Venezuela's alleged failure to
keep its oil commitments.
</P>
<P>
Chavez may also be lobbying with its Latin American neighbors
to obtain a rescheduling of its 23 billion U.S.-dollar debt to the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Mexico, on the other hand, was expected to adopt the same
strategy after being significantly affected by oil revenue
shortfalls in its budget.
</P>
<P>
In Madrid, the three countries reaffirmed their commitment to
the reductions agreed in June in Vienna: 725,000 barrels per day
(bpd) for Saudi Arabia, 525,000 bpd for Venezuela and 200,000 bpd
for Mexico until the end of 1999. But the action did not have a
big influence on the oil prices and new measures to prop up oil
prices are anticipated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
