<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Prosecutor Favors Limited Extradition of Ocalan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah
Ocalan could be extradited to Turkey for charges to which death
penalty cannot be applied, said an Italian prosecutor Monday.
</P>
<P>
Italian public prosecutor Giovanni Malerba told the Rome
Appeals Court that conditions existed to extradite the Kurdish
Worker's Party's (PKK) leader for trial on three of the charges
made in Turkey, but not for the other three because of the
possible death penalty.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor also said he was in favor of some restrictive
measure to ensure Ocalan did not flee Italy before the extradition
process was completed.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan is accused in Turkey of forming and running the outlawed
PKK, attacking the Turkish Constitution, murder, criminal
association, terrorist attacks and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
Malerba told the court that is was important that he be
extradited only for crimes committed before 1991 because,
according to Turkish law, death penalty cannot be applied for
crimes before that date.
</P>
<P>
The crimes for which the Rome prosecutor has suggested
extradition carry a maximum sentence of 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
The Rome Appeals Court on December 16 lifted travel
restrictions on Ocalan, who was arrested in Rome on November 12.
</P>
<P>
The restrictive measures imposed on Ocalan, forbidding him from
leaving the Rome metropolitan area, had in fact been based only on
international warrant issued by Germany.
</P>
<P>
But Germany said that it will not seek to extradite Ocalan to
Germany, for fear of sparking unrest between its own Kurdish and
Turkish immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Italy has refused Turkey's Extradition request because Italian
law bars extradition to countries where defendants could face
death penalty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
