<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government Admits Rape Cases in May Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
Monday admitted that rapes had indeed occurred during the May
rioting, but insisted that their number was not high as had been
previously reported.
</P>
<P>
Minister/State Secretary Akbar Tanjung said 52 women were
raped, 24 others were sexually assaulted, while four more victims
were sexually harassed.
</P>
<P>
He did not give the definitions for rape, sexual assault or
harassment.
</P>
<P>
"According to our investigation, there was no evidence that the
rapes were conducted in an organized way," Akbar said after
meeting with President B.J. Habibie at the Merdeka Palace here.
</P>
<P>
Habibie received Minister of Defense/Armed Forces Chief Gen.
Wiranto, Minister of Muladi and the government representatives of
the government-appointed Joint Fact-Finding Team, which was set up
by the president to investigate the riots which became a decisive
factor for president Soeharto's resignation on May 21.
</P>
<P>
"Victims of the rapes are from various ethnic groups, and are
not only ethnic Chinese as previously rumored," Akbar was quoted
by national newspapers Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the rapes took place in Jakarta, Solo, Surabaya,
Bandung, Palembang and Medan.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the rape cases took place in Jakarta and no rape
victims were killed," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would soon provide compensation and
rehabilitation for rape victims. However, he did not elaborate
further on details of the "compensation and rehabilitation."
</P>
<P>
Human rights groups have said that not less than 117 women,
mostly of Chinese ethnic origin, were raped during the riots.
Nearly 1,200 people were believed to have burned alive as they
were trapped in fires at shopping centers, offices, houses and
public places.
</P>
<P>
The Fact-Finding Team said in its report last month that 52
women, mostly Chinese-Indonesians, were raped. Fourteen of the
women were raped with violence. The team also said that 10 women
who were sexually harassed.
</P>
<P>
The team, led by Chairman of the National Commission on Human
Rights Marzuki Darusman, also found that Soeharto's son-in-law Lt.
Gen. (ret) Prabowo Subianto and former Jakarta military commander
Maj. Gen. Sjafrie Sjamsoeddin might have been involved in the
riots.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki reminded the government not to neglect the search for
those who masterminded the massive riots.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing is the government's promise to fully
investigate the case and those who were involved in the riots," he
said, adding that the credibility of the Indonesian government
depended heavily on its seriousness in solving the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Oil Prices Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) said on Monday that the average price
of its basket of seven crudes remained almost unchanged despite
the three-day U.S. and British air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It stood at 9.78 U.S. dollars last week, compared with 9.42
dollars a week earlier, according to the Vienna-based organization.
</P>
<P>
The average crude oil price last month was 11.19 dollars per
barrel, much cheaper than last year's annual average of 18.68
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Oil experts here noted that the crude oil price would not make
a rebound unless this winter was very cold and long.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC groups Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya,
Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and the United Arab
Emirates.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that OPEC members possess 75 percent of the
world's known reserves of crude oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
