<HEADLINE> Venezuela To Comply With Oil Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President-elect
Hugo Chavez said on Monday his administration would maintain
cooperation with Mexico to prop up oil prices.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference after meeting with President Ernesto
Zedillo, Chavez said that Venezuela would extend its oil cuts
commitments until the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said that in his meeting with Zedillo, he had reaffirmed his
commitment to strengthen the Group of Three, a non-OPEC
(Organization of Petroleum Export Countries) producer which was
made up of crude exporters Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico, .
</P>
<P>
Chavez said that he had also pledged cooperation with Central
America on the basis of the San Jose accords.
</P>
<P>
"The path is not dictatorship, we want democracy," Chavez, a
former army general, said, adding that he rejected authoritarian
militarism and that once he took office in February, a constituent
assembly would be called to make changes benefiting the people.
</P>
</TEXT>
