<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT December 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Iraqi oil exports continued normally despite four
days of bombing by the United States and Britain, according to a
weekly report released by the United Nations Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the week ending Friday, December 18, Iraq shipped 11.14
million barrels of oil under the oil-for-food program, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The export pace of an average of 1.59 million barrels per day
is about normal in comparison with the previous week's 1.7 million
bpd, a U.N. official said. (UN-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton threatened on Monday
to seek tighter sanctions against Libya if it did not turn over
two suspects involved in the 1988 Pan Am bombing for trial in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
"This is a take it or leave it offer," Clinton said during an
Arlington Cemetery ceremony to remember the 270 lives lost in
the Pan Am bombing over Lockerbie, Scotland, 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"We will not negotiate its terms. If the suspects are
convicted, they will serve their time in Scotland. And if the
suspects are not turned over by the time of the next sanctions
review we will work at the United Nations with our allies and
friends to seek yet stronger measures against Libya," he added.
(US-Libya-Lockerbie-Clinton)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudanese National Assembly (parliament) accepted
the resignation of the powerful Speaker, Hassan Abdulla al Turabi,
at a session Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the session, Turabi, who is considered to be the power
behind Sudan's government, said that the purpose of his
resignation is to pave the way for a multi-party mechanism in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Turabi had expressed earlier that he intended to resign as the
speaker and to take up the post of General Secretary of the ruling
National Congress, which will be formally registered as a party in
January next year. (Sudan-Speaker-Resignation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on Monday chaired a
meeting attended by several members of the Revolutionary Command
Council and the ruling Baath party, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time Saddam chaired a meeting since the
four-day U.S.-British air strikes against Iraq came to an end on
Sunday. No detail of the meeting is available. (BC-Iraq-Saddam)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli Knesset (parliament) passed its first
reading Monday of the bill abolishing direct election of prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
The bill was passed by a vote of 62 - 54 in the first reading.
It will be sent back to the Knesset Law Committee for preparations
for its second and thrid readings in the Knesset.
(BC-Israel-Knesset)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz called the
U.S.-British air strikes against Iraq as a "criminal aggression"
aimed at bringing country back to the pre-industrial age.
</P>
<P>
As to the casualties of the army, he said that 62 died and 180
injured.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not give the exact figure of civilian
casualties, saying the damage was similar to that in the 1991 Gulf
War and the almost all the industrial sites were pounded.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. and Britain targeted civilian and government
buildings, radio and TV facilities, communication institutions,
hospitals and schools. (BC-Iraq-Aziz)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian State Secretary/Minister Akbar Tanjung
Monday ruled out the possibility of a meeting between President
B.J. Habibie and his predecessor, Soeharto, for a "national
dialogue."
</P>
<P>
There could never be a meeting among Habibie, former president
Soeharto, Nahdlatul Ulama leader Abdurrahman Wahid and Armed
Forces Commander Gen. Wiranto, Tanjung told reporters at the
presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on Wahid's efforts to bring about a meeting
among the four for a "national dialogue" to solve the nation's
political problems. (Indonesia-Meeting) 
</P>
