<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Inflation Rate Reaches 28.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela will end the year
with an accumulated inflation rate of 28.4 percent, slightly below
the official forecast.
</P>
<P>
The head of the central office of statistics, Miguel Bolivar
Chollett, on Monday said inflation was below government
predictions of 30 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Chollett said the consumer price index would reach 1.6 percent
in December after hitting 1.7 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
He said unemployment averaged 11 percent in the second half of
the year, with over 1.8 million jobless workers.
</P>
<P>
Chollett said that the rate had dropped below the 11.3 percent
joblessness rate registered in the first half.
</P>
<P>
As the slide in the Venezuelan economy continues,
President-elect Hugo Chavez, who will take office on February 2,
will have to tackle a possible currency devaluation due to falling
oil prices, it was reported.
</P>
<P>
Oil is Venezuela's largest source of income and shortfalls in
crude revenues could lead to a 1.6 percent contraction of the
gross domestic product and a budget deficit of nine percent next
year, the country's second straight year of recession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
