<HEADLINE> Investments Plunge 68 Percent in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The government-registered
investments in the Philippines dropped 68.6 percent in the first
11 months of 1998 from a year ago, according to data from the
Board of Investments.
</P>
<P>
Data show that investments during January-November totaled 169
billion pesos (4.225 billion U.S. dollars), a hefty 68.6 percent
drop from 539.67 billion pesos (13.491 billion dollars) posted in
the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In November, the government agency says, investments plunged 88
percent to only 4.2 billion pesos (100 million dollars) from 35.78
billion pesos (894 million dollars) a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The year-to-date investment figure is 231 billion pesos (5.775
billion dollars), falling short of the 400 billion peso (10
billion dollars) target set by the agency.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in investment inflows into the country has been
attributed to the change in the administration this year, with
local and foreign investors "testing the waters" first before
committing to infuse money in a project, the agency says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0292 </DOCNO>
