<HEADLINE> Di Canio Appeals Against Latest Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Absent Sheffield Wednesday
striker Paolo Di Canio has appealed against a fine imposed on him
by his own club.
</P>
<P>
The penalty of two week's wages was issued when Di Canio
refused to return from his native country following compassionate
leave.
</P>
<P>
The Italian had been allowed to return home to be with his
wife and new born baby daughter, but his agent said he has now
been given a doctor's note excusing his absence.
</P>
<P>
The controversial forward has now completed his 11 match ban
served by the FA pushing over referee Paul Alcock during a
Premiership match against Arsenal in September.
</P>
<P>
He is eligible to resume his career on Boxing Day, although
the club said he is unlikely to return for the match against
Leicester.
</P>
<P>
Agent Moreno Roggi said his client was suffering from stress
and depression and was unlikely to fly back until 4 January at
the earliest.
</P>
<P>
Roggi has revealed they have a doctor's certificate verifying
the illness, leaving Wednesday with no grounds to enforce the
suspension.
</P>
<P>
But Wednesday secretary Graham Mackrell said: "He is a
contracted employee of Sheffield Wednesday Football Club and we
are entitled to expect him to work.
</P>
<P>
"There are 206 employees at this club. We don't go looking for
them when they don't turn up. We end up demeaning ourselves."
</P>
<P>
This is the third occasion the club have imposed a fine on Di
Canio, with each penalty the maximum they are allowed to impose.
</P>
<P>
It brings Di Canio's total bill for the affair, including
legal costs, to around 125,000.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday are also threatening to place Di Canio on the
transfer-list with the player still unwilling to talk to them
from his wife's home town of Terni, near Rome.
</P>
<P>
A disciplinary hearing will now be held by the FA next month,
but the Professional Footballers' Association are urging Di Canio
to end his self-imposed exile.
</P>
<P>
Deputy chief executive Brendon Batson said: "The lad has to
come back.
</P>
<P>
"He has a contract with the club and he needs to be honouring
that contract," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
