<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Faith in Euro's Long-Term Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 21 (Xinhua) -- European business leaders
believe the euro currency eventually will overshadow the American
dollar as the world's premier reserve currency within 20 years,
according to a survey released Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some of them, like those from Belgium, Spain and the
Netherlands, predict that the euro's dominance would happen in
just 10 years. Business leaders in the U.K. were the most
pessimistic about the euro's future, with 137 out of 259
executives surveyed doubting it would ever replace the dollar.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,500 business leaders from Europe's top 15,000
companies participated in the survey commissioned by the United
Parcel Service (UPS), a U.S.-based world's largest express carrier
and package delivery company.
</P>
<P>
The London-based Harris International Telephone Research Center
conducted interviewing the executives from Belgium, France,
Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Spain and the U.K. The average
turnover of businesses interviewed is 1.57 billion U.S. dollars
and average employee size is 3,750.
</P>
<P>
UPS said in a report that it conducted the survey to gain
insight into the latest trends and leadership confidence levels in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Despite predictions of the euro's long-term success, UPS said,
only 44 percent of respondents felt the euro introduction would
benefit their companies financially over the next 12 months. In
addition, 51 percent said the euro would make "no difference" in
their companies' performance, and 5 percent believed their firms
would be "worse off" once the euro is introduced next year.
</P>
<P>
The business leaders surveyed also made predictions on the U.S.
economy and expressed views on other issues.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-eight of them predicted a correction for the U.S.
economy over the next 12 months. The instability of the stock
market notwithstanding, nearly one-fifth of respondents believed
the U.S. economy would improve. Germans were the most pessimistic,
with 22 percent believing that the U.S. would suffer a recession
in the next year. In comparison, only 1 percent of all the
business leaders thought the United States is heading for a
depression.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that Europe's business leaders no longer view
Asia as tomorrow's revenue center. While last year nearly a third
looked toward Asia for future growth, this has dropped
dramatically to just 6 percent this year. A booming 66 percent now
see their future growth in Western Europe, led by the Dutch, the
French and the Belgians.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the survey shows the European business leaders
united in their view of the economic crises in Asia, Brazil and
Russia, with the majority of all countries unconcerned about the
impact on European affairs. A total of 78 percent said Brazil's
economic problems would have little or no effect on their
businesses, while 70 percent said the same for Russia and 59
percent for Asia.
</P>
<P>
Global economics ranked highest among six criteria affecting
corporate performance in all countries surveyed, followed by
national political climate, interest rates, EU regulations and the
introduction of the euro. In four of the seven countries surveyed,
more than 50 percent considered global economics the most
influential factor led by Belgium at 64 percent. Germany and the
U.K., while rating global conditions highest, are the least
globally inclined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Parliament Approves State Budget for 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Greek parliament approved
the state budget for 1999 early Tuesday after a five-day debate,
with 161 votes for and 135 votes against.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet, chaired by Prime Minister Costas Simitis, had
approved the budget in November, which aims to help the Greek
government to lower the country's inflation and to join the euro
zone in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
Simitis said before concluding the debate that Greece was
converging with the other European Union countries with its worth.
</P>
<P>
He added that the more the course of the Greek economy
improved, the more the Greek people would be given the price of
their toil. 
</P>
