<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Oil Exports Continue Despite U.S.-British Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi oil exports continued
normally despite four days of bombing by the United States and
Britain, according to a weekly report released by the United
Nations Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the week ending Friday, December 18, Iraq shipped 11.14
million barrels of oil under the oil-for-food program, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The export pace of an average of 1.59 million barrels per day
is about normal in comparison with the previous week's 1.7 million
bpd, a U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
A portion of a refinery in Basra was bombed, but it is not
expected to affect the oil-for-food program, observers said.
</P>
<P>
The program allows Iraq to sell up to 5.256 billion U.S.
dollars of crude oil over six months from November 25 for the
purchase of food, medicine and other humanitarian goods.
</P>
<P>
The program, begun in December 1996, is aimed at alleviating
the suffering of the Iraqi people under U.N. sanctions imposed
after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
