<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Lending to L.America Topples 10 Bln Dlrs in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) Monday announced it has approved a record
10 billion U.S. dollars in loans for Latin America and the
Caribbean during 1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, disbursements to the region also reached a record
6.48 billion dollars during the year.
</P>
<P>
IDB President Enrique V. Iglesias noted in his annual year-end
address to the Board of Executive Directors that despite its new
emergency lending, the largest sector of Bank financing remains
focused on poverty reduction. "The Bank continues to give priority
for programs in the social area," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the IDB had invested heavily in 1998 in
providing relief and assisting reconstruction in those countries
suffering from natural disasters, such as Hurricane Mitch and the
El Nino climate disruption, while continuing to emphasize programs
for reform of the state and improved public management, national
and international peace processes, microenterprise and small
business, regional integration, and gender and ethnic equity.
</P>
</TEXT>
