<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Job Rating up after Impeachment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton's approval ratings have gone up since his impeachment, and
the number of Americans who want him to leave office has gone
down, according to polls released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Three new polls were conducted on Saturday and Sunday after the
impeachment vote in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
New polls by ABC News/Washington Post, CBS News/New York Times
and CNN/USA Today/Gallup mirrored other polls released on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The CBS/Times poll showed Clinton's approval rating at 73
percent after becoming the first president impeached in 130 years,
compared to 68 percent before the vote.
</P>
<P>
The ABC/Post poll had him at 67 percent up from 64 and the
CNN/USA Today poll had 73 percent, up a full 10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The number of people who believe Clinton should remain in
office and not resign or be removed by the Senate has gone up.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of those responding to the CBS/Times poll said
Clinton should remain in office as 31 percent said he should
resign.
</P>
<P>
In the ABC/Post poll, the number of those who said the Senate
should remove him from office went from 39 percent for and 59
against on December 15 to 33 percent for and 66 against on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In responses to the CNN/USA Today poll 68 percent wanted their
senators to vote against conviction while 29 percent wanted them to
vote for, a change of five percentage points in Clinton's favor in
four days.
</P>
<P>
The same poll showed Republican approval dropped drastically.
On December 15-16, Republicans had a favorable rating of 43
percent to 47 percent disapproval, but this weekend that changed
to 31 percent favorable to 57 percent disapproval.
</P>
<P>
Testing suggestions that Americans have not been paying close
attention to the impeachment process, the ABC/Post poll said 82
percent of the people were following the proceedings either "very"
or "somewhat" closely.
</P>
<P>
The ABC/Post poll was conducted among 1,285 adults with a
margin of error of three percentage points, the CBS/Times among
1,341 adults with the same margin of error and the CNN/USA Today
was with 852 adults with a margin of error of four percentage
points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
