<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Pakistan Settle F-16 Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States will pay
Pakistan 326.9 million dollars in cash and up to 140 million
dollars in other compensation to settle an eight-year dispute over
F-16 aircraft that Islamabad paid for but never received, the
White House said in a statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan would receive 324.6 million dollars in cash from the
U.S. Treasury's Judgment Fund and a further 2.3 million dollars
from the U.S. Department of Defense as part of the deal reached by
President Bill Clinton and Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
As part of the 140 million dollars in other compensation, the
United States will give Pakistan white wheat valued at about 60
million dollars at prevailing market prices during the current
U.S. fiscal year, which began on Oct. 1. The other 80 million
dollars in compensation will be negotiated by Washington and
Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
As part of the agreement between Clinton and Sharif, the United
States said Pakistan had agreed to renounce its 463.7 million
dollar claim against the United States for the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft, bought to bolster Pakistan's defenses, were
denied to Pakistan by the U.S. Pressler Amendment which barred
military sales to countries with nuclear programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
