<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Announces Trade Sanctions on Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States Monday
announced it will slap hundreds of millions of dollars of punitive
tariffs on products from the European Union, escalating a banana
trade war between the two.
</P>
<P>
The products covered by the punishment range from sheep's milk
cheese to cashmere sweaters, U.S. Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky announced.
</P>
<P>
The United States was exercising its rights under the World
Trade Organization (WTO) to impose penalties on the 15-nation
Europe Union for, in the U.S. view, unfairly blocking U.S.
companies from selling bananas from Latin America to Europe, said
Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
The penalties, 100 percent tariffs, will effectively double the
price to American consumers of targeted items.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions could go into effect as soon as Feburary. 2, or as
late as March 3, depending on whether the European Union elects to
arbitrate the content of the list.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky said the sanctions list was announced after six
years of failed attempts to get Europe to comply with rulings by
the WTO and its the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT).
</P>
<P>
The tariffs, she said, are intended to offset "the damage
caused by the EU''s discriminatory banana regime."
</P>
<P>
She said "Our door remains open to a negotiated solution" but
as recently as Friday a meeting between Sir Leon Brittan, the
European Union's trade commissioner, and President Clinton and
other administration officials failed to produce an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Among the items targeted for 100 percent tariffs are: Pecorino
cheese made from sheep's milk, sweet biscuits, bath salts,
candles, handbags, felt paper, folding cartons, greeting cards,
lithographs, cashmere sweaters, cotton bed linen, batteries for
electric vehicles, coffee and tea makers and chandeliers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
