<HEADLINE> Romanian Opposition's No-Confidence Motion Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian parliament
Monday evening voted 283-163 to reject the no-confidence motion
put forward by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The no-confidence motion was the first since the new parliament
was formed at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The motion, read out last Wednesday in parliament, was signed
by 97 deputies and 46 senators from the parliamentary groups of
the Party of Social Democracy of Romania (main opposition), the
Greater Romanian Party, and the Romanian National Unity Party.
</P>
<P>
The motion said that Romania is today in the grip of the most
serious social crisis after 1989, referring to "the incapacity of
the current majority to lead the country as well to its incapacity
to understand and defend the national interest."
</P>
<P>
The authors of the no-confidence motion considered that the
government led by Radu Vasile demonstrated in the eight months
since it took office the lack of responsibility for the economic
and social situation in the country."
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Party of Social Democracy Ion Iliescu explained
that the motion was determined by the country's arrested economic
and social development, not political calculations.
</P>
<P>
He said the motion had been meant to "trigger out" serious
public debates on the effects of the current leading coalition's
mistakes and the ways to put an end to the current "dangerous
fall" of economy and living standards, and also to reinvigorate
the country's economy and society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
