<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Lose Radio Contact With NEAR Spacecraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Scientists from the Johns
Hopkins University lost radio contact with a spacecraft trying to
orbit asteroid Eros some 240 millions miles from Earth.
</P>
<P>
Contact was lost about 5 p.m. EST Sunday when scientists at the
university's Applied Physics Laboratory tried to adjust the speed
of the spacecraft so as to lower its speed to enter Eros's orbit,
said spokeswoman Helen Worth Monday.
</P>
<P>
She said that contact was lost during an 18-minute procedure to
fire the main engine of the spacecraft to lower its speed.
Scientists suspect that this procedure was not successful.
</P>
<P>
NEAR was launched into space in 1996 and scientists want it to
circle the asteroid to gather information on Eros and test ways to
save the Earth from killer asteroids.
</P>
<P>
The giant and fast-moving asteroid is 25 mile long. The
spacecraft would orbit and if possible even land on the surface of
the asteroid in 1999 to spend one year to probe its chemistry,
mineral content, mass and density. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
