<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Threatens Tougher Sanction on Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton threatened on Monday to seek tighter sanctions against
Libya if it did not turn over two suspects involved in the 1988
Pan Am bombing for trial in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
"This is a take it or leave it offer," Clinton said during an
Arlington Cemetery ceremony to remember the 270 lives lost in
the Pan Am bombing over Lockerbie, Scotland, 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"We will not negotiate its terms. If the suspects are
convicted, they will serve their time in Scotland. And if the
suspects are not turned over by the time of the next sanctions
review we will work at the United Nations with our allies and
friends to seek yet stronger measures against Libya," he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain in August dropped their
insistence that the Lockerbie suspects be extradited to either of
their countries. They challenged Libya to make good on an offer to
try the suspects in a third country with Scottish law and under a
Scottish court.
</P>
<P>
So far the two suspects, Abdel Basset Ali Mohamed al-Megrahi
and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, have not been handed over.
</P>
<P>
Clinton hoped that Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi might accept
the deal.
</P>
<P>
"That would be the best outcome, for it would mean that
finally there would be a trial," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi earlier said he preferred to set up an international
court with judges from the United States, Britain, Libya and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said if the U.S.-British proposal to try the suspects
in the netherlands fails, Gaddafi will have to bear the
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British envoys told the U.N. Security Council on
Monday that their patience was running out. The Security Council
is scheduled to review sanctions against Libya on February 26.
</P>
<P>
The current sanctions, first enacted in 1992 and reviewed
every 120 days, include a ban on air travel, an arms embargo and
a reduction in the level of diplomatic ties with Libya.
</P>
<P>
They were toughened in 1993 with a freeze on some Libyan
assets abroad and a ban on certain types of equipment used in oil
terminals and at refineries. But there is no embargo on Libya's
oil exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
