<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Hit New Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Oil prices slumped to new lows
on Monday after Iraq's exports survived a four-day military
attacks against Baghdad without disruption.
</P>
<P>
Benchmark North Sea Brent was last traded at $9.76, down 23
cents after crashing to a new 12-year trough of $9.55, five cents
below the previous floor set on December 10.
</P>
<P>
Prices have not been lower since cash Brent slumped below $9 in
the Summer of 1986. Average prices this year are already lower
than in 1986 with Brent running at just $13.42, its cheapest since
1976.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries producer
cartel would have to cut output further to have any chance of a
price rise in 1999, according to the Center for Global Energy
Studies (CGES).
</P>
<P>
"If OPEC wants higher oil prices it must cut production to
achieve them. Protracted delays as we saw in 1998 will only make
the situation worse," the Center said in a monthly report.
</P>
<P>
Western industry officials said four days of air strikes aimed
mainly at Iraqi military targets seemed to have had little direct
impact on the Arab country's export facilities.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi exports were running normally on Monday, said an industry
official familiar with monitoring under a U.N. oil-for-food sales
program said.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq loadings are normal, while on the political side support
for the U.S. and U.K. positions on Iraq is melting away, and that
could point to renewed pressure for a lifting of sanctions,"
Christoper Bellew of Prudential Bache International in London was
quoted by Reuters as saying.
</P>
<P>
Iraq recently has reportedly pumped about 2.5 million barrels a
day of crude, exporting 1.8 million bpd under the U.N.
humanitarian exchange and refining the remainder.
</P>
<P>
The CGES said global demand was expected to have risen only
400,000 bpd in 1998, a mere fifth of 1997's figure.
</P>
<P>
"To cap this dismal news, so far the Winter in the northern
hemisphere has been relatively mild," it said.
</P>
<P>
Prices slumped by more than $1 as a meeting in Madrid last week
between Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico, the architects of two
rounds of oil production cuts this year to shore up prices, ended
without commitments to cut more output.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
