<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Banking sources in Dubai have disclosed that total
revenues of the Gulf budgets this year dropped by 4.3 percent or
68.02 billion dollars, whereas, total expenditures fell by 2.4
percent or 79.32 dollars, as oil revenues dropped by 35 percent
from last year due to the slump of oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Bankers anticipate that deficits in the GCC states budgets will
further deteriorate next year to 20 billion dollars in comparison
with the 11 billion-dollar-deficit in 1998.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Economic circles of the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
have disclosed that UAE economy, its financial and monetary status
as well as its trade activity with the outside world have not been
affected by the U.S.-British attacks against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that the only exception was the suspension of
naval route transporting travelers and cargo between Dubai and the
Iraqi port of Om Qasr which was the target of the recent
U.S.-British military strikes.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Arab Agricultural Services Company (ARASCO) in
Saudi Arabia has recently carried out five new industrial projects
in the central and eastern regions of the country at a total cost
of 200 million Saudi rials (53.3 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The projects cover animal husbandry, food stuff and chemical
industry of the company.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Arab Trade Finance Program has extended a
credit line of 15 million dollars to the Tunisian Central Bank to
enable it to refinance 85 percent of the value of sulphur and
ammonia imports from Libya, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Dhabi-seated Program announced Sunday that it had
signed an agreement with the Tunisian Central Bank in its capacity
as a national agency of the Program. The total credit lines
extended by the Program to Tunisian national agencies amount to
some 88 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
