<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Extends 81.5 Mln Marks of Loan to Georgia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Germany Monday agreed to extend
a loan of 81.5 million Deutsche marks (48.74 million U.S. dollars)
to help the former Soviet republic of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed in Tbilisi by Georgian Finance
Minister David Onoprishvili and German Ambassador Wolf Dietrich
Vogel, the credit was given for 40 years with a 10-year grant
period at an annual interest of 0.75 percent, Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
The accord also envisages the allocation of two other grants,
7.5 million marks (4.5 million dollars) for renovation of
Tbilisi's municipal facilities and services and 1.5 million marks
(900,000 dollars) for education programs.
</P>
<P>
Also Monday, the two countries' signed an agreement on the
protection of environment and natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Under that accord, Germany will provide 5 million marks (3
million dollars) for the reconstruction of Borzhomi-Hkaragauli
National Park in southeastern Georgia.
</P>
<P>
According to the German ambassador, Germany is the second
largest donor after the United States.
</P>
<P>
In 1992-1998, German assistance to Georgia totaled 290 million
marks (173.4 million dollars), Vogel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
