<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Votes for Early Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (parliament)
 Monday passed a bill in the first reading, which calls for
dissolution of Knesset and early elections.
</P>
<P>
The bill was passed by a vote of 80 in favor, 30 against and
four abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Just before the vote, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu made the last efforts to save his government by calling
the opposition Labor Party to join a national unity government.
</P>
<P>
But Labor leader Ehud Barak rejected the offer, saying that
it was too late in the current situation.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel's basic law, the bill will become
legislation after another two readings.
</P>
<P>
However, since most of Knesset members have expressed their
support for the bill, it was almost inevitable that early
elections would be held within six months.
</P>
<P>
The Labor reportedly hoped elections will take place in next
March, while the ruling Likud Party wanted elections in late
April. And the two parties will consult to reach a final date.
</P>
<P>
Besides the two leading party chiefs, another possible
candidate for premiership is the General Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, who
is a popular figure in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Shahak, former Chief of General Staff, is expected to
formally leave the army following Monday's voting and prepare
for the elections.
</P>
<P>
Barak has asked Shahak to be his deputy in the Labor
Party, but Shahak refused and planed to head a centrist party.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest poll in the local media, Barak
may be out of race after the first round of elections. And
only Shahak will compete with Netanyahu for the post of prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has expressed his confidence that he will win in
the elections. During the Knesset plenum, he said that he will
get public mandate for his policy in the peace talks with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Since Netanyahu came to power in June, 1996, the peace process
has been stalled for most of the time in the last two years. And
the opposition left-wing parties accused Netanyahu of dragging
foot in living up to the promises under the Oslo agreement.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the right-wing parties in the coalition
were angry at Netanyahu after he signed a new peace agreement with
the Palestinian on October 23.
</P>
<P>
The protest from both the coalition and the opposition forced
Netanyahu to accept the end of his government. And Netanyahu also
voted for the bill on Monday for early elections, hoping that he
could set up a more stable government next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Range of Ceausescu's Alcoholic Drinks Sold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The last range of Romanian
former president Nicolae Ceausescu's alcoholic drinks was sold by
auction in Bucharest on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The drinks were put out to tender at the Bucur S.A. company's
headoffice, with an opening sale price of 35 million lei (3,300
U.S. dollars), and were sold at last at 150 million lei (14,300
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
As many as 1,150 bottles of wine, spirit, cherry brandy and
champaign were left after the Bucur S.A. company had organized
five bids, putting on sale drinks raised in 1990 from Ceausescu's
Bucharest residence, at the request of the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The oldest wine to be put out to tender was produced in 1918.
Some of the drinks come from former CMEA (the Council of Mutual
Economic Assistance) states or north-African countries, a gift
Ceausescu received from his counterparts, while the others are
domestic ones, part of which were produced in the very cellars of
his villa.
</P>
<P>
Money raised during the auction will be donated to orphanages
and nursing homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981222.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Dialogue Should Prevail in Solving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The 10th anniversary of
the 1988 Lockerbie bombing came Monday, seeing no suspects have
been handed over to the trial before a Scottish court in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the Libyan and the U.K.-U.S. demands remain
wide and the two sides showed no signs for compromise Monday
despite their previous agreements on where to try the two
suspects.
</P>
<P>
However, the world does not lose hope for a positive response
from the Libyan government. The mood was mirrored by Kofi Annan,
who told reporters Monday morning that he is "regrettable, but
still hopeful."
</P>
<P>
"My message to them is that it is regrettable that 10 years
after the event, we have not been able to get to the truth so that
they can put this behind them, mourn their dead and carry on their
lives. But I am still hopeful that we will still get a positive
decision from the Libyan government," the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
"I had hoped it would come before this date -- the anniversary
-- but I have not lost hope. And they (families of victims) should
not" either, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
But the talks have not yet taken place between the Libyan legal
team and the U.N. legal experts despite Tripoli announced that it
would send a legal team to New York for talks with U.N. experts on
the trial of the two suspects of the 1988 Lockerbie bombing, which
killed 270 people after a Pan Am airliner exploded over Lockerbie,
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Washington and London have accused the two Libyans, namely
Lameen Fhaima and Abdel-Basit Al-Megarhi, of masterminding the
bombing 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva told a press
conference Monday, "There was a meeting of the Libyan (General)
People's Congress, and the Libyans have their own mechanisms for
decision-making. And we have to wait on that."
</P>
<P>
Annan, who met with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi on December
5, failed to get the two suspects extradited for a trial before
the Scottish court in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
In August, Tripoli accepted a Washington-London proposal to try
the two under the Scottish law in a neutral country, and this was
seen as a big step forward in efforts to solve the long-standing
issue.
</P>
<P>
At issue is the dispute over where the two suspects, if
convicted, are to serve their sentences. Libya has been demanding
that if the two Libyans are found guilty, they should serve their
sentences in the Netherlands, not in Scotland as Britain and the
United States insist.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, both Britain and the United States warned Libya that
they could take additional measures if it failed by next February
to hand over the two suspects in the case for trial.
</P>
<P>
In his statement during the closed-door Security Council
consultations, Peter Burleigh, charge d'affaires of the U.S.
Mission to the United Nations, said, "We are running out our
patience."
</P>
<P>
"In February, the Security Council will hold its regularly
scheduled review of Libya sanctions," he said. "If by that time,
the government of Libya has not handed over the suspects for trial
before a Scottish court in the Netherlands, we will seek
additional measures to compel compliance."
</P>
<P>
In echoing Burleigh's remarks, Jeremy Greenstock, British
permanent representative to the United Nations, said, "Our
patience is not unlimited. We will ask the Council to look again
at this issue, when it next reviews the sanctions."
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the U.S. concept of "additional
measures" includes a demand for the Security Council to further
tighten its sanctions against Libya, which have already been made
harder on the country under relevant U.N. resolutions adopted in
1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
The warning came as progress has been made around the Lockerbie
issue thanks to the Libyan flexibility and the fruitful mediating
efforts by the Arab League and the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
Practice has proved that only by peaceful efforts, mutual
respect and mutual cooperation are the only effective way to solve
international disputes, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
It is widely accepted that the world is opposed to terrorism in
any form and terrorists should be brought to justice. But the
sanctions do not lead to proper solution to the lengthy problem,
but simply worsen the humanitarian situation in Libya.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged sanctions against Libya have brought untold
sufferings to the Libyan people, especially women and children,
undermined the development of the country, and at the same time
affected the economic growth of third countries.
</P>
<P>
The positive developments around the Lockerbie case should be
helpful for the Security Council to make a decision on an early
lifting of the sanctions against the North African country.
</P>
<P>
Libya has made it clear that Washington and London should not
use the 10th anniversary as a tool of pressure, and the problem
should be solved through dialogue and negotiations. Such a
statement should not be ignored.
</P>
<P>
It is hoped that all parties concerned can, in the spirit of
consultation and cooperation, reach an agreement on the specific
points in the case, thus kicking off the trial process at an early
date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
